1
00:00:09,030 --> 00:00:11,360
[Girl on TV]
You need to talk to your dad.

2
00:00:11,400 --> 00:00:13,030
Ow!

3
00:00:13,070 --> 00:00:15,070
Okay. Okay.

4
00:00:15,100 --> 00:00:17,100
He's not an ogre, ass!

5
00:00:17,140 --> 00:00:20,910
[Girl #2 on TV]
Gee! All right.
I'll talk to him tonight.

6
00:00:20,940 --> 00:00:22,880
Wow.

7
00:00:22,910 --> 00:00:28,150
That's, like, my favorite
right shoulder, ever, I think.

8
00:00:28,180 --> 00:00:30,380
Oh, my God!
It is.

9
00:00:30,420 --> 00:00:32,320
Are you, like, 13?

10
00:00:32,350 --> 00:00:34,790
That's not gonna work.
And besides,

11
00:00:34,820 --> 00:00:36,760
John's gonna be down here
any moment.

12
00:00:36,790 --> 00:00:39,960
No. No, he's not.
We have at least 20 minutes.

13
00:00:39,990 --> 00:00:41,900
I work with the guy.
I've seen it firsthand.

14
00:00:41,930 --> 00:00:44,870
He's one of those clean-freak,
bathroom-phobic types
who take forever.

15
00:00:44,900 --> 00:00:47,730
And even if he didn't,
we're newlyweds, right?

16
00:00:47,770 --> 00:00:50,000
He'll understand.

17
00:00:50,040 --> 00:00:53,170
Still, clean-freak or not,
I hardly want to be the topic

18
00:00:53,210 --> 00:00:55,510
of workplace conversation.

19
00:00:55,540 --> 00:00:58,410
Cubicle conversation
can only go so far.

20
00:00:58,440 --> 00:01:01,150
[toilet flushes]

21
00:01:01,180 --> 00:01:03,280
I win.
[door opens]

22
00:01:05,920 --> 00:01:09,460
John, John, John,
did I mention you'll be, um,

23
00:01:09,490 --> 00:01:11,420
paying for dinner?

24
00:01:13,890 --> 00:01:15,330
[keypad beeping]

25
00:01:15,360 --> 00:01:16,760
[alarm beeping]

26
00:01:16,800 --> 00:01:18,400
[Woman]
Don't beep at me,
you stupid alarm.

27
00:01:18,430 --> 00:01:20,800
The doors are locked.

28
00:01:20,830 --> 00:01:23,840
Well, babe, will you
go check all the doors?

29
00:01:23,870 --> 00:01:27,470
Please, please, please,
please, please?

30
00:01:32,980 --> 00:01:35,520
[lock clicking]

31
00:01:45,990 --> 00:01:50,260
[chattering]
I know where the key is.

32
00:02:13,490 --> 00:02:17,190
[sweater rips]
Oh! Oh, shoot!

33
00:02:17,220 --> 00:02:22,300
Marge, you don't happen to have
your knitting needles with you,
do you?

34
00:02:22,330 --> 00:02:25,170
[indistinct]
I gave up making

35
00:02:25,200 --> 00:02:28,100
and started buying
for that very reason.

36
00:02:28,130 --> 00:02:30,400
Oh, once one thread rips,
the rest will follow.

37
00:02:30,440 --> 00:02:32,170
I just know it.

38
00:02:32,210 --> 00:02:35,180
Why don't you go out
and buy a new sweater
so that doesn't happen?

39
00:02:35,210 --> 00:02:36,610
Buy one?

40
00:02:36,640 --> 00:02:38,280
We don't get paid
till next week,

41
00:02:38,310 --> 00:02:41,350
and my Social Security
don't cover more

42
00:02:41,380 --> 00:02:42,920
than the pantyhose
on my ass.

43
00:02:42,950 --> 00:02:46,250
Bertha, you said
the A-double-S word
in the library.

44
00:02:46,290 --> 00:02:48,020
What's the matter, Marge?

45
00:02:48,050 --> 00:02:49,960
I say a lot of things
in the library

46
00:02:49,990 --> 00:02:52,230
you don't know about.
[laughing]

47
00:02:52,260 --> 00:02:55,630
Next week.
I can't believe I forgot that.

48
00:02:55,660 --> 00:02:58,600
Why, honey,
you need some money?

49
00:03:00,200 --> 00:03:02,840
No. I just didn't
want you to worry.

50
00:03:07,210 --> 00:03:09,510
After these,
you can go.

51
00:03:41,610 --> 00:03:43,980
Why are you always so sad?

52
00:03:46,210 --> 00:03:48,980
[Girl]
You know,
it isn't polite to stare.

53
00:03:49,020 --> 00:03:51,050
Uh, I wasn't staring.

54
00:03:51,080 --> 00:03:52,520
Oh, really?

55
00:03:52,550 --> 00:03:55,420
Then what the fuck
was that thing you were
just doing with your eyes?

56
00:03:55,460 --> 00:03:58,020
You know, that thing where
you wouldn't take them off

57
00:03:58,060 --> 00:03:59,460
those two comatose-looking
people over there?

58
00:03:59,490 --> 00:04:02,660
That's right. Staring.
And it isn't polite.

59
00:04:02,700 --> 00:04:05,170
Especially when they might
be trying to steal something.

60
00:04:05,200 --> 00:04:06,970
[gasps]

61
00:04:07,000 --> 00:04:08,030
[laughing]

62
00:04:10,070 --> 00:04:11,500
[blows raspberry]

63
00:04:33,590 --> 00:04:36,000
[Man]
Hungry for a Papa-Go
Park Picnic Meal?

64
00:04:38,630 --> 00:04:41,430
How much?
Five bucks.

65
00:04:43,240 --> 00:04:45,040
How much for
just the hot dog?

66
00:04:45,070 --> 00:04:46,940
Three bucks.
Hmm.

67
00:05:22,780 --> 00:05:25,650
What, the library now sends
its stupid little shelf-stuffers

68
00:05:25,680 --> 00:05:27,710
to get stolen books back?

69
00:05:29,180 --> 00:05:30,420
No.

70
00:05:32,450 --> 00:05:34,090
What?

71
00:05:36,060 --> 00:05:38,720
[mutters]

72
00:05:38,760 --> 00:05:40,760
I--

73
00:05:40,790 --> 00:05:42,730
I just followed you.

74
00:05:45,170 --> 00:05:47,170
What the fuck?
Are you a pervert?

75
00:05:51,300 --> 00:05:53,210
Are you gonna tell my boss?

76
00:05:53,240 --> 00:05:57,040
No. Not if you tell me
why you followed me,

77
00:05:57,080 --> 00:05:59,180
Alex.

78
00:05:59,210 --> 00:06:02,050
How do you know my name?

79
00:06:04,550 --> 00:06:06,690
After you buy something--

80
00:06:06,720 --> 00:06:08,290
ugh--

81
00:06:08,320 --> 00:06:10,520
make sure it's securely
back in your pocket.

82
00:06:10,560 --> 00:06:12,430
Leave it out like you did,
it's easy to steal.

83
00:06:19,230 --> 00:06:20,770
So?

84
00:06:23,270 --> 00:06:25,170
[Alex]
Don't you look at her

85
00:06:25,210 --> 00:06:27,340
and want to know why
she's like that?

86
00:06:27,370 --> 00:06:30,340
Why she's close
to that dog, but...

87
00:06:33,180 --> 00:06:34,150
recoils from people

88
00:06:34,180 --> 00:06:37,120
like they're the ones
who are going to bite?

89
00:06:38,320 --> 00:06:40,290
Is he really that cool,

90
00:06:41,720 --> 00:06:44,060
or is it an act?

91
00:06:47,130 --> 00:06:49,200
If it's an act, why?

92
00:06:50,560 --> 00:06:54,100
Or this couple in the library--
the Smiths.

93
00:06:54,130 --> 00:06:56,100
They have this routine.

94
00:06:56,140 --> 00:06:57,840
They come in every month

95
00:06:57,870 --> 00:07:00,210
and check out
the same book.

96
00:07:00,240 --> 00:07:03,210
And every time they come in,
they're sad.

97
00:07:03,240 --> 00:07:05,150
Why?

98
00:07:05,180 --> 00:07:07,880
You know,
when I was a little girl,

99
00:07:07,910 --> 00:07:10,180
I used to have a cat.

100
00:07:10,220 --> 00:07:12,220
What happened to it?

101
00:07:12,250 --> 00:07:13,890
Um...

102
00:07:13,920 --> 00:07:16,160
curiosity ran it over.
[chuckles]

103
00:07:16,190 --> 00:07:18,720
Blood and guts were everywhere.
It was really disgusting,
actually.

104
00:07:20,890 --> 00:07:23,230
I-- I have to go.

105
00:07:25,730 --> 00:07:28,430
Okay. I'll just
follow you, then.

106
00:07:29,640 --> 00:07:31,570
[chuckles]

107
00:07:41,180 --> 00:07:43,250
I'm sorry.

108
00:07:43,280 --> 00:07:45,690
Didn't mean to mess up
your nice shit.

109
00:07:48,290 --> 00:07:51,660
Well, if you ever need
a hot girl for a roommate,
just let me know.

110
00:07:51,690 --> 00:07:54,890
I'll move right in.

111
00:07:54,930 --> 00:07:56,900
Where's the fam?

112
00:07:57,960 --> 00:07:59,870
Why'd you steal
the book?

113
00:07:59,900 --> 00:08:02,200
You didn't tell me.

114
00:08:02,240 --> 00:08:04,600
[chuckles]
Well, that wasn't
part of the deal,

115
00:08:04,640 --> 00:08:08,210
but, um, 'cause of my dad.

116
00:08:08,240 --> 00:08:10,480
To win an argument
I had with him.

117
00:08:10,510 --> 00:08:12,410
He's one of those doctors
who refuses to believe

118
00:08:12,450 --> 00:08:14,410
people are actually
how they want to be.

119
00:08:14,450 --> 00:08:17,180
Yeah, shit happens
that fucks them up, but...
I don't know.

120
00:08:17,220 --> 00:08:19,190
Either they wanna get better
or they don't.
It's their choice.

121
00:08:19,220 --> 00:08:20,920
But when they get
with people like him,

122
00:08:20,950 --> 00:08:23,190
it doesn't happen.
Why?

123
00:08:23,220 --> 00:08:25,360
'Cause now they're hooked
on stupid gimmicks.

124
00:08:25,390 --> 00:08:28,430
Told to find out what their
real problem is when they
knew it in the first place.

125
00:08:28,460 --> 00:08:30,400
They just couldn't
fucking face it.

126
00:08:30,430 --> 00:08:31,860
Now they're looking
for different solutions.

127
00:08:31,900 --> 00:08:33,900
Shit that isn't possible,
but, um,

128
00:08:33,930 --> 00:08:36,940
'cause of people like him,
they're convinced it is.

129
00:08:36,970 --> 00:08:39,310
That's why you steal books?

130
00:08:39,340 --> 00:08:41,270
I steal whatever.

131
00:08:41,310 --> 00:08:42,880
I figured since I was
his daughter

132
00:08:42,910 --> 00:08:44,510
and so clearly fine,

133
00:08:44,540 --> 00:08:46,510
he would have to know
there's no bigger issue.

134
00:08:46,550 --> 00:08:47,980
So what happened?

135
00:08:48,010 --> 00:08:51,350
Now I'm addicted
to stealing shit.

136
00:08:51,380 --> 00:08:53,420
But whatever. Who cares?

137
00:08:53,450 --> 00:08:56,990
I won...I think.

138
00:08:57,020 --> 00:08:58,320
Well, I wouldn't
have known that

139
00:08:58,360 --> 00:08:59,830
if I hadn't followed you.

140
00:09:13,540 --> 00:09:15,640
[Alex]
Why are they back the next day?

141
00:09:17,310 --> 00:09:20,410
Oh, my. You really
like this one, huh?

142
00:09:20,450 --> 00:09:22,550
I can probably
special order it if you like.

143
00:09:22,580 --> 00:09:24,880
No. We like
to come and get it.

144
00:09:24,920 --> 00:09:26,820
It gets us
out of the house.

145
00:09:26,850 --> 00:09:29,620
[Mr. Smith]
Actually, this will be
the last time we check it out.

146
00:09:29,660 --> 00:09:32,860
I think we've finally
had our fill.

147
00:09:32,890 --> 00:09:34,730
Right, honey?

148
00:09:42,900 --> 00:09:44,000
[footsteps approaching]

149
00:09:44,040 --> 00:09:47,040
[Mr. Smith]
Where are you going?
Shh.

150
00:09:47,070 --> 00:09:48,870
What's wrong?

151
00:09:50,340 --> 00:09:52,750
Honey?
Nothing.

152
00:09:54,350 --> 00:09:56,320
Thank you.
[Bertha]
You're welcome.

153
00:09:56,350 --> 00:09:59,520
[Mr. Smith]
Have a good day.
You, too. Bye.

154
00:11:09,420 --> 00:11:11,090
Breathe, Alice, breathe.

155
00:11:14,730 --> 00:11:17,460
It's been a year.

156
00:11:17,500 --> 00:11:19,600
You have to try.

157
00:11:21,770 --> 00:11:23,640
You can't keep doing this.

158
00:11:24,700 --> 00:11:26,640
[sniffles]

159
00:12:03,610 --> 00:12:05,580
[gasps]

160
00:12:05,610 --> 00:12:08,950
[Mr. Smith]
What? What's going on?

161
00:12:08,980 --> 00:12:10,950
Honey, what's wrong?

162
00:12:10,980 --> 00:12:13,590
Are you okay?

163
00:12:13,620 --> 00:12:16,920
Honey, what?
What happened?

164
00:12:45,150 --> 00:12:47,520
[Mrs. Smith]
I thought I saw him.

165
00:12:49,150 --> 00:12:51,520
[Mr. Smith]
It will stop, honey.
You know it will.

166
00:12:51,560 --> 00:12:53,590
When?

167
00:12:53,630 --> 00:12:57,730
We have taken a big step
this week, and the rest
will follow.

168
00:12:57,760 --> 00:13:00,730
By packing him away
like one of your sports cards?

169
00:13:00,770 --> 00:13:03,040
By erasing any evidence
that he was ever here?

170
00:13:03,070 --> 00:13:05,870
That is not a first step.
Then what is?

171
00:13:05,910 --> 00:13:08,070
You tell me.
What is a first step, Alice?

172
00:13:08,110 --> 00:13:09,580
Because I would really
like to know.

173
00:13:09,610 --> 00:13:12,080
Doing nothing?
Never changing?

174
00:13:12,110 --> 00:13:14,010
I didn't say that.
Well, then, what--

175
00:13:14,050 --> 00:13:15,950
what are you saying?

176
00:13:15,980 --> 00:13:18,150
What are you saying?

177
00:13:18,180 --> 00:13:21,120
It's hard.
You don't understand.

178
00:13:21,150 --> 00:13:22,860
I'll tell you what
I don't understand, Alice.

179
00:13:22,890 --> 00:13:25,660
I don't understand
why you keep going in there.

180
00:13:25,690 --> 00:13:28,560
I don't understand why you
keep cleaning his laundry

181
00:13:28,590 --> 00:13:30,230
again and again.

182
00:13:30,260 --> 00:13:32,870
I don't understand why you
keep torturing yourself...
No! No!

183
00:13:32,900 --> 00:13:35,540
Yes! Yes! Yes!
No, you cannot touch the...

184
00:13:35,570 --> 00:13:39,570
No! You have your
stupid office closet.

185
00:13:39,610 --> 00:13:41,510
I have this.

186
00:13:41,540 --> 00:13:43,510
What? You think I don't know
what you do in there?

187
00:13:43,540 --> 00:13:47,250
Why you miss your deadlines?
Hey, at least I'm still working.

188
00:13:47,280 --> 00:13:49,150
Oh, that's right.

189
00:13:49,180 --> 00:13:52,280
Me going back to the flower
shop's gonna solve everything,
isn't it?

190
00:13:52,320 --> 00:13:54,620
Not everything.
It's just...

191
00:13:54,650 --> 00:13:56,660
[gasps]

192
00:13:56,690 --> 00:13:58,590
I'm sorry.

193
00:13:58,620 --> 00:14:00,530
I--I thought
this was my house.

194
00:14:00,560 --> 00:14:02,930
I--I got lost.
I'm sorry.

195
00:14:02,960 --> 00:14:04,730
[Alice]
Wait!

196
00:14:11,900 --> 00:14:13,540
Eat as much
as you want.

197
00:14:13,570 --> 00:14:15,540
There's a week's worth
in the fridge.

198
00:14:16,910 --> 00:14:18,780
Why didn't you call
the police?

199
00:14:20,580 --> 00:14:22,650
You reminded me of my son.

200
00:14:22,680 --> 00:14:25,650
Oh, yeah?

201
00:14:25,690 --> 00:14:28,620
How old is he?
Is he home?

202
00:14:31,260 --> 00:14:33,660
He's dead.

203
00:14:37,130 --> 00:14:39,900
It was a terrible disease.

204
00:14:43,740 --> 00:14:45,610
Your parents are dead,
too, aren't they?

205
00:14:50,940 --> 00:14:53,910
I can see it in your eyes.

206
00:14:59,120 --> 00:15:01,290
I have to go.

207
00:15:03,120 --> 00:15:07,630
Thanks for the food
and for not calling the cops.

208
00:15:08,690 --> 00:15:10,660
I don't know
how this happened.

209
00:15:10,700 --> 00:15:12,600
It looked like my house
from outside.

210
00:15:12,630 --> 00:15:14,200
Would you like
to see his picture?

211
00:15:17,770 --> 00:15:21,240
This is Timmy
before he got sick.

212
00:15:21,270 --> 00:15:23,940
Uh, he was 16 there.

213
00:15:31,650 --> 00:15:35,590
He was actually much bigger
than he looks in that photo.

214
00:15:40,160 --> 00:15:43,000
[alarm beeps]

215
00:15:43,030 --> 00:15:45,030
Oh, I'm sorry.

216
00:15:45,060 --> 00:15:48,000
I'm supposed to watch
my Dr. Alred videos now.

217
00:15:48,030 --> 00:15:49,900
Is that okay?

218
00:15:51,240 --> 00:15:53,210
Yeah, it's fine.

219
00:15:55,370 --> 00:15:56,810
[TV on]

220
00:15:58,840 --> 00:16:00,710
[Dr. Alred on TV]
Hello, and welcome back.

221
00:16:00,750 --> 00:16:02,950
I hope you've seen
some progress within yourself

222
00:16:02,980 --> 00:16:04,250
since last we spoke.

223
00:16:04,280 --> 00:16:07,790
If so, you're one step further
in this terrible journey

224
00:16:07,820 --> 00:16:09,890
known as
the five stages of grief.

225
00:16:09,920 --> 00:16:12,390
And what one are we on?

226
00:16:12,420 --> 00:16:14,690
Depression.

227
00:16:14,730 --> 00:16:17,200
I want you to think
about your loved one

228
00:16:17,230 --> 00:16:20,170
and recall one happy memory.

229
00:16:20,200 --> 00:16:22,740
But don't get sad
about what isn't.

230
00:16:22,770 --> 00:16:27,740
Instead, celebrate what was
and cherish that.

231
00:16:27,770 --> 00:16:31,780
If you can do this,
then you are ready.

232
00:16:31,810 --> 00:16:35,110
But if you can't, then you
need to restart this disc

233
00:16:35,150 --> 00:16:38,350
and reflect on exactly
why you're feeling

234
00:16:38,380 --> 00:16:40,790
the way you are.

235
00:16:42,050 --> 00:16:45,120
Which one, honey? There are
so many to choose from.

236
00:16:45,160 --> 00:16:47,090
It's up to you.

237
00:16:49,390 --> 00:16:51,860
Ah. I got it.
The perfect one.

238
00:16:51,900 --> 00:16:54,770
This will tell you the kind of
crazy imagination Timmy had.

239
00:16:54,800 --> 00:16:57,100
He was, uh--
He was about eight,

240
00:16:57,140 --> 00:16:58,500
and he had just gotten home
from a sleepover

241
00:16:58,540 --> 00:17:01,970
where they had stayed
up all night watching
scary movies, and--

242
00:17:02,010 --> 00:17:03,880
Not this one.

243
00:17:05,780 --> 00:17:08,050
But it's a good one.
Please?

244
00:17:09,950 --> 00:17:11,320
Do what you want.

245
00:17:14,950 --> 00:17:16,820
[door closes]

246
00:17:18,420 --> 00:17:20,390
He, um--

247
00:17:20,430 --> 00:17:24,830
He acts like he doesn't like
to talk about Timmy, but...

248
00:17:24,860 --> 00:17:27,200
I know what he does
in his office.

249
00:17:31,000 --> 00:17:33,210
What was the movie?

250
00:17:33,240 --> 00:17:35,170
Well, it was, uh...

251
00:17:35,210 --> 00:17:37,740
It was one of those
monster ones.

252
00:17:37,780 --> 00:17:40,880
You know,
where they steal you away,
take over your body.

253
00:17:40,910 --> 00:17:42,820
I can't remember.
Something like that.

254
00:17:42,850 --> 00:17:46,950
But what I do remember
was the look on his face.

255
00:17:48,020 --> 00:17:50,860
