at that stage now.

512
00:33:55,190 --> 00:33:57,090
Good night.

513
00:34:00,420 --> 00:34:03,460
I think these are worse off
than when you gave them to me.

514
00:34:03,490 --> 00:34:05,760
[chuckles]
Men.

515
00:34:05,800 --> 00:34:07,230
Let me show you.

516
00:34:07,270 --> 00:34:09,870
Nothing is worse off

517
00:34:09,900 --> 00:34:10,970
after someone
has cared for it.

518
00:34:11,000 --> 00:34:12,740
Those were.

519
00:34:12,770 --> 00:34:14,370
Nothing.

520
00:34:17,110 --> 00:34:18,980
Timmy was the same
at first.

521
00:34:20,880 --> 00:34:24,420
He sat out here complaining,
but he got good,

522
00:34:24,450 --> 00:34:27,120
just like you will.

523
00:34:27,150 --> 00:34:30,250
That's where he would sit
and watch you, wasn't it?

524
00:34:33,960 --> 00:34:35,030
Yes.

525
00:34:39,130 --> 00:34:41,200
So what does Mark do?

526
00:34:41,230 --> 00:34:43,870
Um, he writes for
a sports Web site.

527
00:34:43,900 --> 00:34:45,800
He used to write
for a bigger column,

528
00:34:45,840 --> 00:34:46,910
but he switched
to a smaller one

529
00:34:46,940 --> 00:34:49,210
so that he could write
from here and take care
of me.

530
00:34:50,340 --> 00:34:52,110
He doesn't get a lot
of writing done.

531
00:34:52,140 --> 00:34:54,110
Mostly,
he just keeps himself

532
00:34:54,150 --> 00:34:56,050
locked up in that
damn office closet,

533
00:34:56,080 --> 00:34:58,450
which is off-limits to me.

534
00:35:04,960 --> 00:35:06,390
Mark?

535
00:35:18,900 --> 00:35:20,910
I'm not in there.

536
00:35:20,940 --> 00:35:22,910
Uh, Alice said
you were looking for me.

537
00:35:22,940 --> 00:35:24,410
I thought you might be.

538
00:35:24,440 --> 00:35:26,340
All right. Are you right
or left-handed?

539
00:35:26,380 --> 00:35:27,580
Right-handed.
Okay.

540
00:35:27,610 --> 00:35:30,880
So, that's what
your grip looks like.

541
00:35:30,920 --> 00:35:32,820
Bring it up to your ear.

542
00:35:32,850 --> 00:35:35,020
As you throw,
it comes off like that.

543
00:35:38,860 --> 00:35:40,120
Did we miss anything?

544
00:35:40,160 --> 00:35:42,130
Beginning credits
just ended.

545
00:35:42,160 --> 00:35:43,960
[Woman on TV]
I'm Miss Childs,

546
00:35:44,000 --> 00:35:47,970
and I'll be filling in
as your substitute.

547
00:35:48,000 --> 00:35:50,030
You pick first, sweetie.

548
00:35:50,070 --> 00:35:52,170
I can choose
whatever I want?

549
00:36:02,580 --> 00:36:04,850
Monopoly.

550
00:36:07,390 --> 00:36:08,990
Monopoly?

551
00:36:10,550 --> 00:36:12,320
Monopoly's perfect.

552
00:36:14,390 --> 00:36:15,830
I know.

553
00:36:32,410 --> 00:36:33,910
Oh!
No, no, no, no.

554
00:36:33,950 --> 00:36:36,880
Seven, eight, nine!
[all laugh]

555
00:36:43,220 --> 00:36:45,890
[Man on TV]
See you later.

556
00:36:45,920 --> 00:36:49,630
[Woman]
Honey, maybe you can go to
New York for graduate school.

557
00:36:49,660 --> 00:36:52,200
[TV continues, indistinct]

558
00:36:54,230 --> 00:36:56,100
[grunting]

559
00:36:59,570 --> 00:37:01,640
[grunting]

560
00:37:10,950 --> 00:37:14,120
Is all that prodding you do
to him really necessary?

561
00:37:14,150 --> 00:37:16,390
Stretching is essential
if he's gonna get any better.

562
00:37:16,420 --> 00:37:18,320
Not if it's gonna hurt him,
and that hurts him.

563
00:37:18,360 --> 00:37:22,060
Okay, then, what else
do you want me to do?
Magically heal him?

564
00:37:22,090 --> 00:37:24,400
I'd like you to be
a little more careful.

565
00:37:24,430 --> 00:37:26,100
When have I
not been careful?

566
00:37:26,130 --> 00:37:27,400
I'm not gonna
argue about this.

567
00:37:27,430 --> 00:37:30,700
Really, when have I
not been careful?

568
00:37:30,730 --> 00:37:34,070
They don't look that much
different from yesterday.

569
00:37:34,110 --> 00:37:37,080
But they feel it.
I mean, I can probably get up
and walk right now.

570
00:37:37,110 --> 00:37:38,710
No, sweetie.
You're not ready.

571
00:37:38,740 --> 00:37:40,980
Let's wait until tomorrow
as planned,

572
00:37:41,010 --> 00:37:45,120
and if they still feel
this good, we'll get you up.

573
00:37:45,150 --> 00:37:48,090
But with crutches.

574
00:37:48,120 --> 00:37:49,190
Yeah.

575
00:38:07,510 --> 00:38:11,140
Alex! I'm home!

576
00:38:11,180 --> 00:38:13,210
Did you hear? That was me
breaking the fuck in!

577
00:38:13,240 --> 00:38:17,150
You're lucky it wasn't your face
for making me come back here
for days!

578
00:38:17,180 --> 00:38:19,980
[chuckles]
Neigh.

579
00:38:20,020 --> 00:38:21,650
** [rock]

580
00:38:21,690 --> 00:38:24,390
Fine.
I'm just gonna wait here

581
00:38:24,420 --> 00:38:27,690
until you decide
to man up and come out
from wherever you're hiding.

582
00:38:31,130 --> 00:38:32,560
You pussy.

583
00:38:32,600 --> 00:38:36,070
I bet I'm the first girl
you ever had in your bed.

584
00:38:36,100 --> 00:38:39,100
Disgusting.

585
00:38:40,240 --> 00:38:43,270
[Alice]
You know,
you don't have to leave.

586
00:38:43,310 --> 00:38:45,710
Even after you're better,
you can stay.

587
00:38:45,740 --> 00:38:48,710
I'll still make you
your special meal.

588
00:38:48,750 --> 00:38:51,050
I just wanna finish this.

589
00:38:52,220 --> 00:38:54,690
You've been pushing me away
all day. Why?

590
00:38:54,720 --> 00:38:56,350
I have to finish it.

591
00:38:56,390 --> 00:38:58,660
You don't have
to do anything.

592
00:38:58,690 --> 00:39:01,160
We would never make you do
something you didn't wanna do.

593
00:39:01,190 --> 00:39:04,130
Well, you're not
my parents.

594
00:39:09,070 --> 00:39:11,170
Tell me about them.

595
00:39:11,200 --> 00:39:13,640
I don't remember them.

596
00:39:13,670 --> 00:39:15,740
Everybody remembers
their parents.

597
00:39:15,770 --> 00:39:17,580
Not me.

598
00:39:17,610 --> 00:39:20,510
Well, don't you think
that's a little weird?

599
00:39:21,810 --> 00:39:24,220
Are you sure you're not
mad at me about something?

600
00:39:24,250 --> 00:39:27,190
Look, please just
leave me alone.

601
00:39:27,220 --> 00:39:30,550
I'm out of here tomorrow,
and then you don't have
to worry about me.

602
00:39:31,620 --> 00:39:33,260
It's gonna be okay.

603
00:39:33,290 --> 00:39:35,090
No, Mark.

604
00:39:35,130 --> 00:39:37,130
Just let me think.

605
00:39:40,100 --> 00:39:42,030
What's going on?

606
00:39:46,100 --> 00:39:48,210
He doesn't remember them.

607
00:40:39,190 --> 00:40:41,190
[Man]
Why don't you sit down
at the table

608
00:40:41,230 --> 00:40:43,190
and have some dinner, Alex?

609
00:40:43,230 --> 00:40:46,230
[Alex]
I'm not hungry.
Fine.

610
00:40:46,260 --> 00:40:48,770
You wanna talk to us
about this report card, then?

611
00:40:48,800 --> 00:40:52,170
What is it gonna take
for you to get off my back,
fucking die?

612
00:40:52,200 --> 00:40:53,670
[Woman]
You're horrible, awful.

613
00:40:53,700 --> 00:40:55,840
Only an awful person
would say such a thing.

614
00:40:55,870 --> 00:40:57,780
Get back here, Alex.
[door opens]

615
00:40:57,810 --> 00:41:00,110
Get back in this house, Alex!
[door closes]

616
00:41:01,180 --> 00:41:03,610
Mom? Dad?

617
00:41:03,650 --> 00:41:07,220
Dad? Mom?

618
00:41:07,250 --> 00:41:10,190
It's okay, honey.
You're okay. Let it out.
[sobbing]

619
00:41:10,220 --> 00:41:11,290
No, not this time.

620
00:41:11,320 --> 00:41:13,290
Let me go.
No.

621
00:41:13,320 --> 00:41:17,600
I don't like to let things
that are good out of my life.
Do you?

622
00:41:17,630 --> 00:41:19,560
Then why should I?

623
00:41:21,670 --> 00:41:25,240
Especially when I have something
that's gonna cheer you up.

624
00:41:27,340 --> 00:41:28,670
They look good.

625
00:41:28,710 --> 00:41:30,570
"Good"?

626
00:41:31,880 --> 00:41:35,150
Morning. Ready to do
some walking?

627
00:41:36,650 --> 00:41:37,820
They're more than good.

628
00:41:37,850 --> 00:41:39,250
They're--
They're your favorite.

629
00:41:40,320 --> 00:41:42,650
No, bacon and eggs
are my favorite.

630
00:41:42,690 --> 00:41:45,190
But these are okay, too.

631
00:41:46,320 --> 00:41:48,230
What's going on, Alice?

632
00:41:48,260 --> 00:41:50,190
Well, I made him
his favorite breakfast food,

633
00:41:50,230 --> 00:41:52,230
hoping that it would
help him remember, but he...

634
00:41:52,260 --> 00:41:54,330
These-- These are okay.

635
00:41:54,370 --> 00:41:55,330
Really.

636
00:41:57,640 --> 00:42:00,340
It's all right, Alex.
I see what's happening.

637
00:42:00,370 --> 00:42:02,870
Do you?
Because it's so obvious.

638
00:42:02,910 --> 00:42:06,380
It's-- It's so obvious,
yet no one seems to see it.

639
00:42:06,410 --> 00:42:08,350
You're upset because
he's leaving today,

640
00:42:08,380 --> 00:42:10,380
so upset that you
accidentally

641
00:42:10,410 --> 00:42:13,350
made him Timmy's
favorite food,
not Alex's.

642
00:42:13,380 --> 00:42:15,750
No. No, that is not it.

643
00:42:15,790 --> 00:42:20,290
I bet if you take one bite,
it will help you remember.

644
00:42:20,320 --> 00:42:22,560
That's all it takes.
You know, just--

645
00:42:22,590 --> 00:42:25,260
just-- just
a familiar thing

646
00:42:25,300 --> 00:42:27,230
to help you remember.

647
00:42:29,430 --> 00:42:32,370
Just like
all those obvious signs
that you showed me.

648
00:42:32,400 --> 00:42:35,940
Listen. Here.
[doorbell rings]

649
00:42:35,970 --> 00:42:37,910
What can we do
for you, Father?

650
00:42:37,940 --> 00:42:41,310
Well, me and the other fathers
have taken it upon ourselves

651
00:42:41,350 --> 00:42:44,250
to reach out
to the member base--

652
00:42:44,280 --> 00:42:47,350
to the ones who haven't
been led in prayer recently.

653
00:42:47,390 --> 00:42:49,290
And according to the directory,

654
00:42:49,320 --> 00:42:51,290
it's been over a year
since you've been in,

655
00:42:51,320 --> 00:42:54,360
so I wanted to come on down
and re-invite you

656
00:42:54,390 --> 00:42:56,660
to services at St. Matthews.

657
00:42:56,690 --> 00:42:58,460
And how is Timmy?

658
00:42:58,500 --> 00:43:01,930
Has the Lord struck
the sickness out of him yet?

659
00:43:01,970 --> 00:43:04,670
He's getting better. Yes.
It's sweet of you to wonder.

660
00:43:06,840 --> 00:43:09,340
Ah! There he is.

661
00:43:09,370 --> 00:43:11,480
Hello, Timmy.
How are you?

662
00:43:11,510 --> 00:43:14,780
[Alice]
He's grown shy
since the disease.

663
00:43:14,810 --> 00:43:17,750
He doesn't feel comfortable
in his own skin.

664
00:43:19,950 --> 00:43:22,420
Uh, Father, we were--

665
00:43:22,450 --> 00:43:24,360
we were sort of
in the middle of something.

666
00:43:24,390 --> 00:43:26,290
So if there's nothing else...
I'm sorry.

667
00:43:26,320 --> 00:43:28,360
No, no.
Uh, thank you.

668
00:43:28,390 --> 00:43:30,290
Excuse me.
Have a good day.

669
00:43:32,700 --> 00:43:34,800
What the hell
are you doing?
Shh!

670
00:43:34,830 --> 00:43:37,030
You don't want the priest
to hear you swearing like that.

671
00:43:37,070 --> 00:43:39,040
Why doesn't he know
Timmy is dead?

672
00:43:41,040 --> 00:43:44,070
Oh, sweetie, no one knows.

673
00:43:44,110 --> 00:43:46,580
We didn't see the point
of telling anyone when we--

674
00:43:46,610 --> 00:43:48,580
we knew you
were coming back.

675
00:43:48,610 --> 00:43:51,010
You've escaped
from the monsters.

676
00:43:51,050 --> 00:43:53,880
Returned like you said
you would.

677
00:43:57,020 --> 00:43:58,490
Alice...
Mark.

678
00:43:58,520 --> 00:44:00,860
Alice, stop.

679
00:44:00,890 --> 00:44:02,330
See?

680
00:44:08,370 --> 00:44:09,930
It's my fault.

681
00:44:09,970 --> 00:44:12,400
It's mine.

682
00:44:12,440 --> 00:44:14,570
I should've known sooner.

683
00:44:14,610 --> 00:44:16,910
Maybe if I had, you wouldn't
have gotten hurt again.

684
00:44:16,940 --> 00:44:20,380
I shouldn't have stayed.
I was selfish.

685
00:44:20,410 --> 00:44:22,550
Oh, Timmy,
you had no choice.

686
00:44:22,580 --> 00:44:23,980
You were drawn to it.
It's your house.

687
00:44:25,380 --> 00:44:27,890
I'm not Timmy.

688
00:44:28,950 --> 00:44:30,790
Well, of course, you are.

689
00:44:30,820 --> 00:44:32,960
Listen. Look, you, uh--

690
00:44:32,990 --> 00:44:35,360
You knew where you used
to sit in the garden,

691
00:44:35,390 --> 00:44:36,390
you knew your favorite game

692
00:44:36,430 --> 00:44:37,800
was Monopoly...
Alice!

693
00:44:37,830 --> 00:44:39,400
Enough!

694
00:44:46,770 --> 00:44:48,640
[grunts]
Let me help.

695
00:44:48,670 --> 00:44:50,710
You're not ready.

696
00:44:50,740 --> 00:44:51,680
[vase shatters]

697
00:44:53,680 --> 00:44:56,410
You're not ready.
[screams]

698
00:44:56,450 --> 00:44:58,920
[sniffling]

699
00:45:02,950 --> 00:45:06,460
We failed, didn't we?
We lost him again.

700
00:45:06,490 --> 00:45:10,990
No. Alice,
Alex is not dead.

701
00:45:11,030 --> 00:45:12,760
Now, I have
bandaged his feet.

702
00:45:12,800 --> 00:45:14,400
The paramedics can do
the rest when they get here.

703
00:45:14,430 --> 00:45:17,940
You called an ambulance?
I'm calling one, and then
I'm calling a doctor for you.

704
00:45:17,970 --> 00:45:21,540
How could you do that
after everything that
he has told us and shown us?

705
00:45:21,570 --> 00:45:24,610
You used to believe
that he would come back.

706
00:45:27,550 --> 00:45:29,680
I was shock--
We were in shock.

707
00:45:29,710 --> 00:45:32,750
Two parents believing
in their son is not shock,

708
00:45:32,780 --> 00:45:34,420
it's love.

709
00:45:34,450 --> 00:45:35,620
No.

710
00:45:35,650 --> 00:45:37,520
Read this.

711
00:45:39,560 --> 00:45:42,460
"Dear Mom and Dad,
I can't do this to you anymore.

712
00:45:42,490 --> 00:45:45,530
"You both are too good
of parents to deserve
the pain I've caused you.

713
00:45:45,560 --> 00:45:47,500
"I'll come back
when I'm better.

714
00:45:47,530 --> 00:45:49,470
Love, Timmy."

715
00:45:58,840 --> 00:46:01,210
This was in the vase?
Yes.

716
00:46:01,240 --> 00:46:03,580
You saw it.
He knocked the vase down.

717
00:46:03,610 --> 00:46:05,080
He broke it. Why?

718
00:46:05,120 --> 00:46:06,950
Because he put a note
in there a year ago,

719
00:46:06,980 --> 00:46:09,750
knowing it was my favorite vase,
but we never found it.

720
00:46:09,790 --> 00:46:11,620
So he showed us.

721
00:46:11,660 --> 00:46:14,190
He's trying to tell us it's him,
even if he doesn't know it yet,

722
00:46:14,220 --> 00:46:17,700
and we have to listen.

723
00:46:17,730 --> 00:46:20,830
It's not possible.
I want it to be,
but it's not--

724
00:46:20,860 --> 00:46:22,770
Just think about
what's happened.

725
00:46:22,800 --> 00:46:24,540
That's all I'm asking.

726
00:46:24,570 --> 00:46:28,170
He tries to leave,
and he gets hit,

727
00:46:28,210 --> 00:46:30,540
and then we get another chance
to realize it's him.

728
00:46:30,570 --> 00:46:31,540
And I do.

729
00:46:31,580 --> 00:46:33,810
So does the priest,
a man of God.

730
00:46:33,840 --> 00:46:36,750
But still, we argue,
and what happens?

731
00:46:36,780 --> 00:46:39,580
He gets hurt again.

732
00:46:39,620 --> 00:46:43,090
We can't keep denying it.

733
00:46:44,990 --> 00:46:47,120
If we do,

734
00:46:47,160 --> 00:46:50,830
the next time he leaves,
we won't be so lucky.

735
00:46:51,900 --> 00:46:54,230
And neither will he.

736
00:47:05,140 --> 00:47:08,150
[bird chirping]

737
00:47:08,180 --> 00:47:10,610
[Alice]
It's singing for us, sweetie.

738
00:47:10,650 --> 00:47:14,220
Singing because
it's so happy.

739
00:47:22,960 --> 00:47:24,760
[chuckles]

740
00:47:24,800 --> 00:47:26,860
You need a haircut,
Timmy.

741
00:47:27,930 --> 00:47:30,670
It's gotten too long.

742
00:47:30,700 --> 00:47:32,200
We'll, um...

743
00:47:32,240 --> 00:47:34,540
get you all fixed up
after you're feeling better.

744
00:47:34,570 --> 00:47:36,670
How's that sound?

745
00:47:36,710 --> 00:47:38,680
I'm, uh...
I'm not Timmy.

746
00:47:38,710 --> 00:47:40,810
[Mark]
Whoa. Easy there, champ.

747
00:47:40,840 --> 00:47:43,280
You need to stay calm,
all right?

748
00:47:43,310 --> 00:47:46,620
This will be worse
than a tackle.

749
00:47:46,650 --> 00:47:48,650
And he's taken plenty
of those.

750
00:47:48,690 --> 00:47:50,620
Okay? Trust me.

751
00:47:50,650 --> 00:47:53,120
Trust me, buddy.
You just...

752
00:47:53,160 --> 00:47:55,130
[panting]
You'd much rather get this

753
00:47:55,160 --> 00:47:58,130
than have me stitch you up
without it.

754
00:47:58,160 --> 00:48:01,570
[Alice]
Shh, shh, shh!
I can't move!

755
00:48:01,600 --> 00:48:04,570
[grunts, mutters]

756
00:48:04,600 --> 00:48:07,200
Shhhh!

757
00:48:07,240 --> 00:48:10,270
We can't have you hurting
yourself again.

758
00:48:10,310 --> 00:48:12,940
We need to make sure
you're safe.

759
00:48:38,670 --> 00:48:40,600
[dial tone]

760
00:48:41,870 --> 00:48:44,240
What's wrong?

761
00:48:44,270 --> 00:48:46,810
That was Alex's mother.

762
00:48:46,840 --> 00:48:49,210
She called me a monster.

763
00:48:49,250 --> 00:48:53,180
She said he was safe at home
and never coming back.

764
00:48:53,220 --> 00:48:54,180
Oh!

765
00:48:54,220 --> 00:48:56,750
How is he?
Sleeping.

766
00:48:56,790 --> 00:49:00,190
I'm just getting his pain pills
together for the week.

767
00:49:01,790 --> 00:49:05,130
Is everything else
taken care of?

768
00:49:05,160 --> 00:49:07,060
Yeah.

769
00:49:07,100 --> 00:49:09,770
He, uh, should be safe.

770
00:49:09,800 --> 00:49:12,040
No way a burglar
could get in or out.

771
00:49:12,070 --> 00:49:14,300
How about a safecracker?

772
00:49:18,280 --> 00:49:21,980
I don't know what's worse,
the knee injury or his feet.

773
00:49:22,010 --> 00:49:24,680
I mean, 50 stitches
can't be pleasant.

774
00:49:26,080 --> 00:49:27,990
Honey, he'll play again.

775
00:49:38,760 --> 00:49:41,030
Morning, bright eyes.

776
00:49:41,060 --> 00:49:43,300
You look happy to see me.

777
00:49:43,330 --> 00:49:46,700
Your, uh, father's gonna come
on in and check your bandages,

778
00:49:46,740 --> 00:49:48,170
but I wanted
to come in first.

779
00:49:48,210 --> 00:49:51,740
You okay?
[footsteps approaching]

780
00:49:58,720 --> 00:50:01,720
It's okay.
It's the anesthetic.

781
00:50:01,750 --> 00:50:04,220
Dries your mouth out
the first day.

782
00:50:04,250 --> 00:50:06,690
My poor baby.

783
00:50:08,030 --> 00:50:10,860
Here. Um...

784
00:50:10,890 --> 00:50:15,300
Why don't you write down,
oh, what you're thinking?

785
00:50:18,070 --> 00:50:20,870
There you go.

786
00:50:20,900 --> 00:50:22,740
I'll hold it for you.

787
00:50:33,420 --> 00:50:35,020
Done?

788
00:50:40,790 --> 00:50:43,760
Let's get you back in.

789
00:50:43,790 --> 00:50:45,700
I know. I know.

790
00:50:46,900 --> 00:50:49,900
There we go.
All safe and sound.

791
00:50:54,870 --> 00:50:57,310
It's not very nice.

792
00:50:57,340 --> 00:50:59,240
It's not nice at all.

793
00:50:59,280 --> 00:51:01,210
And we raised you better.

794
00:51:12,490 --> 00:51:15,390
[locks clicking]

795
00:51:21,100 --> 00:51:23,730
Going through your shirts!

796
00:51:27,270 --> 00:51:28,770
Ugh.

797
00:51:28,810 --> 00:51:31,010
[gasps]
Oh, sparkly.

798
00:51:34,810 --> 00:51:37,050
I'm stealing
your jewelry box.

799
00:51:40,950 --> 00:51:43,020
[sighs]

800
00:51:43,050 --> 00:51:45,260
Consider it payment for making
me come back here for days

801
00:51:45,290 --> 00:51:47,360
when I could've been stealing
other people's shit.

802
00:51:53,000 --> 00:51:55,030
I want to...

803
00:51:56,200 --> 00:51:57,970
move.

804
00:51:58,000 --> 00:52:00,140
What?
Move.

805
00:52:03,370 --> 00:52:05,340
Um, okay.

806
00:52:05,380 --> 00:52:08,050
Okay, but you can't
tell Alice, okay?

807
00:52:08,080 --> 00:52:09,910
We'll just stay
in here.

808
00:52:09,950 --> 00:52:11,380
Deal?

809
00:52:21,930 --> 00:52:24,930
Oh, you see?
See how much better
your knees are?

810
00:52:24,960 --> 00:52:27,230
You couldn't bend them
like that three days ago.

811
00:52:30,100 --> 00:52:32,170
So, uh...

812
00:52:32,200 --> 00:52:34,100
So, uh, I didn't know.

813
00:52:34,140 --> 00:52:38,010
I mean, you hadn't talked
about it, but had you--

814
00:52:38,040 --> 00:52:41,080
Had you still wanted
to go there?

815
00:52:41,110 --> 00:52:43,910
Because if you did,
I'll bet

816
00:52:43,950 --> 00:52:45,920
if you got back in shape
in the next six months,

817
00:52:45,950 --> 00:52:49,450
you could still make
the fall tryouts.

818
00:52:49,490 --> 00:52:50,890
Please.

819
00:52:52,020 --> 00:52:54,160
Let me leave.

820
00:53:02,030 --> 00:53:04,500
Don't-- Don't put any weight
on your feet.

821
00:53:04,530 --> 00:53:07,200
You don't want those stitches
popping out.

822
00:53:10,910 --> 00:53:12,040
[door closes]

823
00:53:12,080 --> 00:53:14,180
[lock clicks]

824
00:53:42,110 --> 00:53:44,910
What do you think?

825
00:53:56,450 --> 00:54:00,060
You're not mad
that I took everything
out of storage, are you?

826
00:54:31,120 --> 00:54:34,090
[sprinkler whirring]

827
00:54:45,140 --> 00:54:47,440
[locks clicking]

828
00:54:47,470 --> 00:54:51,110
Look at what
I made for you.

829
00:54:51,140 --> 00:54:53,610
Mark!
What is he doing up?

830
00:54:53,640 --> 00:54:56,150
He's not ready!

831
00:54:56,180 --> 00:54:58,120
See?
He has hurt himself already.

832
00:54:58,150 --> 00:54:59,480
I thought if he
could move around--

833
00:54:59,520 --> 00:55:01,650
You have to let me go.

834
00:55:01,680 --> 00:55:03,990
Please.

835
00:55:04,020 --> 00:55:06,420
People are expecting me.

836
00:55:06,460 --> 00:55:08,590
People I work with.

837
00:55:08,630 --> 00:55:11,130
The monsters?
Don't worry, sweetie.

838
00:55:11,160 --> 00:55:13,000
I told them
that you were home,

839
00:55:13,030 --> 00:55:14,360
and that you're
not coming back.

840
00:55:14,400 --> 00:55:16,070
They can't hurt
you anymore.

841
00:55:16,100 --> 00:55:19,440
I'm not home.
This isn't my home.

842
00:55:19,470 --> 00:55:22,370
This is how
you treat your parents

843
00:55:22,410 --> 00:55:24,570
when they try
to help you?

844
00:55:24,610 --> 00:55:27,440
I'm not--
Don't even think
about saying

845
00:55:27,480 --> 00:55:29,610
such hurtful things.

846
00:55:31,280 --> 00:55:33,180
Please.

847
00:55:33,220 --> 00:55:35,320
I'm not your son.

848
00:55:41,620 --> 00:55:43,990
Check his feet
and get him in bed.

849
00:55:55,170 --> 00:55:58,480
I do not like treating you
like you are six again,

850
00:55:58,510 --> 00:56:01,380
but since nasty things have been
coming out of your mouth,
you leave me no choice.

851
00:56:01,410 --> 00:56:04,510
[coughing]
I want you to lay here and think
about what you've done.

852
00:56:04,550 --> 00:56:08,290
I will be back at 10:00,
and it better be a clean mouth
that I return to.

853
00:56:08,320 --> 00:56:11,250
[panting]

854
00:56:11,290 --> 00:56:14,090
[locks clicking]

855
00:56:22,330 --> 00:56:25,540
Hi. Uh, this is Mark Smith
for Dr. Nance.

856
00:56:25,570 --> 00:56:27,670
Please, call me Jack.

857
00:56:27,700 --> 00:56:30,440
We have, after all,
met many times before.

858
00:56:30,470 --> 00:56:33,640
No, we haven't.
I've never met you before.

859
00:56:33,680 --> 00:56:37,150
Why would you say that when,
in fact, we have, several times?

860
00:56:37,180 --> 00:56:39,150
Don't you remember
I used to come here

861
00:56:39,180 --> 00:56:41,280
for your family's
counseling sessions?

862
00:56:41,320 --> 00:56:44,450
I know I've probably put on
a few love pounds,
as I like to call them,

863
00:56:44,490 --> 00:56:46,790
but surely I don't look
that much different
from last year.

864
00:56:46,820 --> 00:56:51,260
My name is Alex Wells.

865
00:56:51,290 --> 00:56:54,260
I'm not their son.

866
00:56:54,300 --> 00:56:58,100
I look like him,
but it's not me.
He's dead.

867
00:57:00,470 --> 00:57:04,210
Do you know why
your father called me?

868
00:57:04,240 --> 00:57:08,580
Your family has relapsed,
and he asked me to intervene.

869
00:57:08,610 --> 00:57:09,880
Last time,
it was for them--

870
00:57:09,910 --> 00:57:13,150
for the difficulty
they were having
in dealing with your illness.

871
00:57:13,180 --> 00:57:15,350
It was quite simply
destroying them.

872
00:57:15,390 --> 00:57:17,220
We're passed that now.

873
00:57:17,250 --> 00:57:19,520
We've accepted it,
and we're here only
for him.

874
00:57:19,560 --> 00:57:22,190
Absolutely.
That's right.

875
00:57:22,230 --> 00:57:24,460
Please.

876
00:57:24,490 --> 00:57:25,830
You don't understand.

877
00:57:25,860 --> 00:57:28,170
Tell me,
what am I not understanding?

878
00:57:28,200 --> 00:57:31,170
That I'm not Timmy.

879
00:57:31,200 --> 00:57:32,900
They're trying
to make me into him.

880
00:57:32,940 --> 00:57:35,570
I told you, he's dead.

881
00:57:35,610 --> 00:57:39,280
Could it be that maybe that's
what you feel deep inside,

882
00:57:39,310 --> 00:57:41,280
that you're dead,

883
00:57:41,310 --> 00:57:43,350
and that's why you've
taken on this other persona?

884
00:57:43,380 --> 00:57:45,650
It's not a persona.

885
00:57:47,880 --> 00:57:50,720
They lock me in a room.

886
00:57:51,790 --> 00:57:53,760
They tie me to a bed.

887
00:57:53,790 --> 00:57:56,160
Those are medical restraints.
We don't like using them.

888
00:57:56,190 --> 00:57:58,160
We only use them
when he's sleeping.

889
00:57:58,200 --> 00:58:00,900
But he's continually
trying to hurt himself.

890
00:58:00,930 --> 00:58:03,700
Like his feet.
He tried to go out
the front door the other day.

891
00:58:03,730 --> 00:58:05,870
I knew he wasn't ready.
He lost his balance,

892
00:58:05,900 --> 00:58:08,270
knocked over a vase,
and he fell onto
the broken glass.

893
00:58:08,310 --> 00:58:11,910
You can't believe this.
Don't believe this.
Look at his face.

894
00:58:11,940 --> 00:58:15,310
I see concern
on his face, Timmy.

895
00:58:15,350 --> 00:58:17,410
Now, I may not condone
the methods,

896
00:58:17,450 --> 00:58:19,280
but if you're gonna try
to hurt yourself,

897
00:58:19,320 --> 00:58:20,880
what choice do they have?

898
00:58:20,920 --> 00:58:23,190
Put you in
a medical facility?

899
00:58:23,220 --> 00:58:24,950
Someone has
to take care of you,

900
00:58:24,990 --> 00:58:28,590
and wouldn't you prefer
that it be them?

901
00:58:28,630 --> 00:58:31,430
I think the reason
that he's retreated
into this other persona

902
00:58:31,460 --> 00:58:33,800
is out of fear
of what's happening to him.

903
00:58:33,830 --> 00:58:35,970
For him to come out,
he needs to feel assured

904
00:58:36,000 --> 00:58:38,270
that it's okay
to live as Timmy again.

905
00:58:38,300 --> 00:58:40,370
But how do we do that?

906
00:58:40,400 --> 00:58:41,670
Make things comfortable.

907
00:58:41,700 --> 00:58:45,940
Remind him that it's okay
and fun to live as Timmy.

908
00:58:45,980 --> 00:58:47,610
We--
Even with his disability.

909
00:58:47,640 --> 00:58:49,280
We have. I have.

910
00:58:49,310 --> 00:58:50,580
We've, uh--

911
00:58:50,610 --> 00:58:52,280
We've done some
of his favorite things

912
00:58:52,320 --> 00:58:53,950
to make him feel
at home.

913
00:58:53,980 --> 00:58:56,290
He even chose some,
like Monopoly

914
00:58:56,320 --> 00:58:57,990
or his favorite movie.

915
00:58:58,020 --> 00:59:01,390
Yes, yes, but who was he
during those times?

916
00:59:01,420 --> 00:59:03,390
Alex.
Exactly.

917
00:59:03,430 --> 00:59:05,830
He's living the good things
as Alex,

918
00:59:05,860 --> 00:59:07,660
completely forgetting
that he used to experience

919
00:59:07,700 --> 00:59:10,230
those exact same things
as Timmy.

920
00:59:10,270 --> 00:59:12,240
And they were still good.

921
00:59:12,270 --> 00:59:14,240
So we need to show him
that he can have fun

922
00:59:14,270 --> 00:59:15,710
and enjoy things
as Timmy.

923
00:59:15,740 --> 00:59:17,040
But you must be firm.

924
00:59:17,070 --> 00:59:20,380
He may not remember
that something used to be
his favorite thing.

925
00:59:20,410 --> 00:59:23,650
Blocked it out so he can
experience it new as Alex.

926
00:59:23,680 --> 00:59:25,350
Don't let him.

927
00:59:25,380 --> 00:59:27,550
Be firm,
like you would a child.

928
00:59:27,580 --> 00:59:29,790
And hopefully, in time,
he'll come out of his shell

929
00:59:29,820 --> 00:59:33,520
and remember, "Hey,
it's okay to be Timmy."

930
00:59:34,920 --> 00:59:36,830
Is that okay
with you, Timmy?

931
00:59:36,860 --> 00:59:40,630
Participating in sessions
with your parents?

932
00:59:40,660 --> 00:59:44,400
If I do, could I try sleeping
without restraints

933
00:59:44,430 --> 00:59:47,300
and having my door unlocked?

934
00:59:47,340 --> 00:59:49,040
Well, if you promise
not to hurt yourself,

935
00:59:49,070 --> 00:59:52,310
and your parents are comfortable
with where you are,

936
00:59:52,340 --> 00:59:54,340
I don't see why not.

937
01:00:00,050 --> 01:00:01,980
Thank you.

938
01:00:03,390 --> 01:00:04,920
For?

939
01:00:04,950 --> 01:00:07,020
For calling Dr. Nance.

940
01:00:07,060 --> 01:00:09,360
Mmm.

941
01:00:09,390 --> 01:00:10,430
I gotta tell you,

942
01:00:10,460 --> 01:00:13,060
I was really starting
to lose it.

943
01:00:13,100 --> 01:00:15,400
Just having him
in our grasp

944
01:00:15,430 --> 01:00:18,440
and not knowing
how to bring him back,

945
01:00:18,470 --> 01:00:20,400
what else to do.

946
01:00:22,370 --> 01:00:25,540
Wanna see the first exercise
I have planned?

947
01:00:26,710 --> 01:00:30,380
Then plant this exactly
where you used to.

948
01:00:31,450 --> 01:00:33,780
And, Timmy,
no funny business.

949
01:00:33,820 --> 01:00:36,620
I'll be watching to make sure
you do it right.

950
01:00:49,570 --> 01:00:51,500
[door opens]

951
01:00:57,870 --> 01:00:59,480
Okay.

952
01:01:02,040 --> 01:01:04,080
Where would Timmy plant?

953
01:01:29,170 --> 01:01:32,780
Come on, Timmy.
Stop fooling around.

954
01:01:37,680 --> 01:01:39,480
[glass shatters]

955
01:01:58,500 --> 01:01:59,400
[glass shatters]

956
01:02:22,890 --> 01:02:24,830
[glass crunching]

957
01:02:28,030 --> 01:02:29,770
[glass shatters]

958
01:03:02,970 --> 01:03:05,470
Pick your player.

959
01:03:13,510 --> 01:03:15,910
That's enough, young man.

960
01:03:15,950 --> 01:03:18,880
Pick the piece
you always use.

961
01:03:29,590 --> 01:03:31,990
Alice, stop. Your hand...
I don't care.

962
01:03:32,030 --> 01:03:34,830
I'm not playing around anymore.

963
01:03:34,860 --> 01:03:36,930
Which you clearly still are.

964
01:03:36,970 --> 01:03:38,640
But that's fine.

965
01:03:38,670 --> 01:03:40,570
I'm gonna be firm.
I need to be.

966
01:03:40,600 --> 01:03:42,510
And if I get hurt
in the process,

967
01:03:42,540 --> 01:03:44,710
then at least
you'll see the pain
your little game is causing.

968
01:03:46,180 --> 01:03:48,810
Now, go again.

969
01:04:18,880 --> 01:04:20,680
Very good.
[relieved sigh]

970
01:04:20,710 --> 01:04:25,050
Now, you two,
let's have some fun.

971
01:04:25,080 --> 01:04:29,020
** [rock]

972
01:04:35,120 --> 01:04:37,030
* Got a jonesin'
for the 'Mats *

973
01:04:37,060 --> 01:04:39,230
* For the Pixies,
for the Smiths, REM *

974
01:04:39,260 --> 01:04:41,560
* For the Cure
They knew how to play *

975
01:04:41,600 --> 01:04:43,230
* Playin' drunk,
playin' loud *

976
01:04:43,270 --> 01:04:46,070
* It's the sound of underground
Rockin' out with my pals *

977
01:04:46,100 --> 01:04:47,740
* Class of '91

978
01:04:47,770 --> 01:04:49,740
[knock at door]

979
01:04:49,770 --> 01:04:51,610
[Man]
Josie?

980
01:04:51,640 --> 01:04:53,810
Volume knobs were invented
so that fathers

981
01:04:53,840 --> 01:04:56,810
could get work done
in the other room.

982
01:04:56,850 --> 01:04:58,750
[door rattles]

983
01:04:58,780 --> 01:05:01,280
Why is your door locked?

984
01:05:01,320 --> 01:05:03,290
Did you steal
something again?

985
01:05:03,320 --> 01:05:06,660
[sighs]
Just your heart, Father.

986
01:05:06,690 --> 01:05:09,560
Good.
Keep it that way.

987
01:05:12,390 --> 01:05:14,730
* Back in college,
rock meant something
more than money *

988
01:05:14,760 --> 01:05:16,600
* More than majors,
more than fashion *

989
01:05:16,630 --> 01:05:18,600
* More than merch,
more than TRL *

990
01:05:18,640 --> 01:05:20,900
** [continues, indistinct]

991
01:05:24,740 --> 01:05:27,340
* They are pushing
these lame new bands *

992
01:05:27,380 --> 01:05:30,850
* Whose modern-day noises
I can't understand *

993
01:05:30,880 --> 01:05:33,850
Then you're gonna spend
the day with your father.

994
01:05:35,250 --> 01:05:37,790
You excited?

995
01:05:37,820 --> 01:05:39,760
You should be.

996
01:05:39,790 --> 01:05:43,160
He's been in his office
preparing for your exercise.

997
01:05:43,190 --> 01:05:46,000
And, uh, don't worry.

998
01:05:46,030 --> 01:05:48,800
I figured out a way
to make sure you don't
get hurt again.

999
01:05:49,870 --> 01:05:52,740
[Alice]
He's all yours.

1000
01:05:52,770 --> 01:05:54,040
I am going shopping.

1001
01:05:54,070 --> 01:05:55,840
Bye, honey.

1002
01:05:58,940 --> 01:06:00,780
[Mark]
You have a good night's sleep?

1003
01:06:00,810 --> 01:06:01,810
[Alex]
Yeah.

1004
01:06:01,840 --> 01:06:03,110
Best one yet.

1005
01:06:03,150 --> 01:06:04,850
Good. Good.

1006
01:06:04,880 --> 01:06:08,050
So, um, you--you probably
didn't have a chance

1007
01:06:08,080 --> 01:06:10,750
to see yesterday's
scores yet.

1008
01:06:10,790 --> 01:06:13,290
In fact, you--
you probably haven't had
a chance to catch up

1009
01:06:13,320 --> 01:06:15,960
with the scores
from this past year

1010
01:06:15,990 --> 01:06:19,130
since things have been
so weird for you
and all, huh?

1011
01:06:19,160 --> 01:06:21,830
No, I haven't, but, uh,
I'm dying to know.

1012
01:06:21,860 --> 01:06:22,930
Trust me.

1013
01:06:24,170 --> 01:06:27,070
Then wait until
you see this.

1014
01:06:41,950 --> 01:06:44,350
I started it
when I had to...

1015
01:06:44,390 --> 01:06:48,090
give up on you
coming back.

1016
01:06:48,120 --> 01:06:50,230
There's a section for

1017
01:06:50,260 --> 01:06:54,030
all your favorite baseball,
basketball, and football teams,

1018
01:06:54,060 --> 01:06:56,800
and every game,
every score,

1019
01:06:56,830 --> 01:06:59,070
every standing
from the past year.

1020
01:06:59,100 --> 01:07:01,770
All your favorite
athletes, too.

1021
01:07:01,800 --> 01:07:03,810
It's all here.

1022
01:07:04,870 --> 01:07:08,340
[chuckles]
See that one?

1023
01:07:08,380 --> 01:07:11,850
I must've read
that one 500 times.

1024
01:07:11,880 --> 01:07:14,750
Every time I did, I...

1025
01:07:14,780 --> 01:07:18,220
I could hear how excited
you would've been.

1026
01:07:18,250 --> 01:07:21,420
It had to seem like
you were still almost here.

1027
01:07:28,800 --> 01:07:30,900
You still know.

1028
01:07:30,930 --> 01:07:32,840
You know
this isn't right, Mark.

1029
01:07:32,870 --> 01:07:34,300
You know it's not me.

1030
01:07:34,340 --> 01:07:36,410
Listen. Just--Just listen.
Listen to me.

1031
01:07:36,440 --> 01:07:39,380
They're down by one,
and all they need's
a field goal.

1032
01:07:39,410 --> 01:07:41,040
You know?
Just...

1033
01:07:41,080 --> 01:07:42,380
And it's raining.

1034
01:07:42,410 --> 01:07:44,050
Just let me go
before she gets back, please.

1035
01:07:44,080 --> 01:07:45,210
Listen to me.
Please.

1036
01:07:45,250 --> 01:07:46,750
It's great.
They're down by one.

1037
01:07:50,520 --> 01:07:53,960
You, uh, shampooed
your hair yet, sweetie?

1038
01:07:53,990 --> 01:07:55,790
I was just about to.

1039
01:07:55,830 --> 01:07:57,260
Let me.

1040
01:08:01,500 --> 01:08:05,770
Do you know why your father
is sitting in his office upset?

1041
01:08:05,800 --> 01:08:07,440
Because I do.

1042
01:08:07,470 --> 01:08:10,440
I was in there,
assuming you were doing good,

1043
01:08:10,470 --> 01:08:12,840
continuing to make progress.

1044
01:08:12,880 --> 01:08:14,840
And then he told me
what you said.

1045
01:08:14,880 --> 01:08:16,510
I can explain. It was--
Rinse.

1046
01:08:16,550 --> 01:08:18,180
[water sloshing]

1047
01:08:18,210 --> 01:08:20,020
[Alex gasping]

1048
01:08:20,050 --> 01:08:22,550
To me it sounded
like you wanted to leave.

1049
01:08:22,580 --> 01:08:27,020
That for every step forward,
you were taking a step back.

1050
01:08:27,060 --> 01:08:28,960
Did you say it?

1051
01:08:28,990 --> 01:08:30,890
You missed a spot,
sweetie.

1052
01:08:30,930 --> 01:08:32,330
[water sloshing]

1053
01:08:32,360 --> 01:08:33,860
[Alex gasping]

1054
01:08:33,900 --> 01:08:36,330
Yes or no?
[coughing]

1055
01:08:36,370 --> 01:08:39,140
Yes!

1056
01:08:39,170 --> 01:08:42,270
I, uh, was feeling bad,
looking at all that stuff.

1057
01:08:42,300 --> 01:08:44,270
[coughing]

1058
01:08:44,310 --> 01:08:46,280
Knowing what I missed
this past year, you know?

1059
01:08:46,310 --> 01:08:49,280
I got scared and relapsed.

1060
01:08:53,250 --> 01:08:55,150
That's better.

1061
01:08:55,180 --> 01:08:57,120
It won't happen again.

1062
01:09:01,560 --> 01:09:04,390
[Woman on TV]
I'm Miss Childs,
and I'll be filling in...

1063
01:09:04,430 --> 01:09:07,000
We're watching this again?
I like this movie.
It's really funny.

1064
01:09:07,030 --> 01:09:08,830
So if you'll take
your books out...

1065
01:09:08,870 --> 01:09:10,800
What is it?

1066
01:09:13,340 --> 01:09:16,110
It's the movie
we watched last week

1067
01:09:16,140 --> 01:09:18,840
when I pretended
to be Alex.

1068
01:09:18,880 --> 01:09:21,040
[Girl on TV]
Miss Shane had
a whole party planned.

1069
01:09:21,080 --> 01:09:22,880
And what is your name,
young lady?

1070
01:09:22,910 --> 01:09:24,910
But that's not
the first time
I've seen it.

1071
01:09:24,950 --> 01:09:28,050
I've seen this movie,
uh, a bunch of times.

1072
01:09:28,080 --> 01:09:30,220
Well, there's nothing...

1073
01:09:30,250 --> 01:09:33,020
This is not just a movie
you've seen a bunch of times.

1074
01:09:33,060 --> 01:09:35,390
This is your favorite movie.

1075
01:09:35,420 --> 01:09:38,090
I know that.

1076
01:09:38,130 --> 01:09:41,260
Then why didn't you say that
to begin with, young man?

1077
01:09:41,300 --> 01:09:42,900
Why do you act
as if you saw it

1078
01:09:42,930 --> 01:09:44,930
for the first time
last week?

1079
01:09:48,470 --> 01:09:50,540
[Mark]
Come on, champ.

1080
01:09:50,570 --> 01:09:54,240
You know this.
You remember this.

1081
01:09:57,050 --> 01:09:59,880
I relapsed.
I didn't meant to, but I--

1082
01:09:59,920 --> 01:10:03,150
You swore that
that would never happen again.

1083
01:10:04,690 --> 01:10:06,120
It won't.

1084
01:10:08,260 --> 01:10:11,360
Then what is it called?

1085
01:10:11,390 --> 01:10:14,260
[chattering on TV]

1086
01:10:18,970 --> 01:10:20,640
You wanna keep testing me?

1087
01:10:20,670 --> 01:10:22,940
Then you will stay in here
and watch this movie

1088
01:10:22,970 --> 01:10:24,870
until Thursday
with no food.

1089
01:10:26,080 --> 01:10:27,610
But today's Monday.

1090
01:10:27,640 --> 01:10:29,550
Don't blame me.
This is your own doing.

1091
01:10:29,580 --> 01:10:31,950
You blew your chance
at easy, fun-time exercises.

1092
01:10:31,980 --> 01:10:34,650
Now, I will be in
every two hours to reset it,

1093
01:10:34,680 --> 01:10:38,150
and each time
I catch you sleeping,
it will be an extra day.

1094
01:10:40,990 --> 01:10:44,360
[Miss Childs on TV]
I'm Miss Childs,
and I'll be filling in

1095
01:10:44,390 --> 01:10:45,490
as your substitute.

1096
01:10:45,530 --> 01:10:46,560
[door slams]

1097
01:10:47,960 --> 01:10:50,500
[latches unlocking]

1098
01:10:50,530 --> 01:10:53,540
[TV: long, sustained beep]

1099
01:10:53,570 --> 01:10:56,110
[thunderclap]

1100
01:11:00,340 --> 01:11:03,150
[Miss Childs on TV]
I'm Miss Childs,
and I'll be filling in

1101
01:11:03,180 --> 01:11:05,250
as your substitute.

1102
01:11:05,280 --> 01:11:07,720
So if you'll take
your books out and turn--

1103
01:11:07,750 --> 01:11:09,590
[door slams]

1104
01:11:09,620 --> 01:11:11,720
[latches unlocking]

1105
01:11:11,750 --> 01:11:14,390
[Girl on TV]
Um, today's, like,
my last day.

1106
01:11:14,420 --> 01:11:16,960
Miss Shane had
a whole party planned.

1107
01:11:16,990 --> 01:11:19,230
And what is your name,
young lady?

1108
01:11:19,260 --> 01:11:22,330
Heather.
I'm the class president.

1109
01:11:25,100 --> 01:11:29,110
Well, there's nothing here
in my notes about a party.

1110
01:11:29,140 --> 01:11:31,110
Why is this your last day?

1111
01:11:31,140 --> 01:11:34,680
'Cause my daddy got a big-time
job at a new lawyers firm.

1112
01:11:34,710 --> 01:11:36,010
We're, like, moving...

1113
01:11:39,080 --> 01:11:42,320
[TV: long, sustained beep]

1114
01:11:45,320 --> 01:11:48,220
I'm Miss Childs,
and I'll be filling in

1115
01:11:48,260 --> 01:11:50,060
as your substitute.

1116
01:11:52,130 --> 01:11:55,100
[Bertha]
But I'm hoping against
that thing called hope

1117
01:11:55,130 --> 01:11:58,130
that once he gets readjusted
to being home again,

1118
01:11:58,170 --> 01:12:01,600
his mother'll let him
come back and work with us.

1119
01:12:01,640 --> 01:12:04,410
I don't know.
She did call you a monster.

1120
01:12:07,210 --> 01:12:08,510
Hello?

1121
01:12:08,540 --> 01:12:11,480
Are you two fine-ass bitches
high off books?

1122
01:12:11,510 --> 01:12:13,320
I just said his mother
is dead.

1123
01:12:13,350 --> 01:12:15,320
[gasps]
Whoever called, it wasn't her.

1124
01:12:15,350 --> 01:12:18,150
I know what this is.
I saw it on the news.

1125
01:12:18,190 --> 01:12:20,560
Unkempt girls like her
go around

1126
01:12:20,590 --> 01:12:24,560
trying to convince others
to give information.

1127
01:12:24,590 --> 01:12:27,300
It's called, uh...
[stammering]

1128
01:12:27,330 --> 01:12:29,100
[mimicking stammering]

1129
01:12:29,130 --> 01:12:31,270
Identity theft.
That's it.

1130
01:12:31,300 --> 01:12:33,540
And she did have his ID.

1131
01:12:33,570 --> 01:12:36,810
Bertha, call the police
and let them have her.
Hello?

1132
01:12:36,840 --> 01:12:38,640
[pounding]
Why don't you just
go and help Marco?

1133
01:12:38,670 --> 01:12:40,140
[bell dinging]
Go on.

1134
01:12:40,180 --> 01:12:42,310
Three weeks ago,
she called...

1135
01:12:42,340 --> 01:12:45,180
Pooh on you again!
[bell dinging]

1136
01:12:50,550 --> 01:12:53,190
[Heather on TV]
Um, today's, like, my last day.
[latches unlocking]

1137
01:12:53,220 --> 01:12:55,790
Miss Shane had
a whole party planned.

1138
01:12:55,820 --> 01:12:58,160
And what is your name,
young lady?

1139
01:12:58,190 --> 01:13:00,100
Heather.
I'm the class president.

1140
01:13:00,130 --> 01:13:02,530
Time's up, young man.

1141
01:13:02,560 --> 01:13:05,600
You done horsing around,
or do we leave you here
for another day?

1142
01:13:05,630 --> 01:13:08,100
Well, there's nothing here
in my notes about a party.

1143
01:13:08,140 --> 01:13:09,840
Why is this
your last day?
Done.

1144
01:13:09,870 --> 01:13:13,110
'Cause my daddy got a big-time
job at a new lawyers firm.

1145
01:13:13,140 --> 01:13:16,110
We're, like, moving
into a better home.

1146
01:13:16,150 --> 01:13:18,110
He says I'll be--

1147
01:13:26,390 --> 01:13:28,620
Thank you...

1148
01:13:29,860 --> 01:13:30,790
Mom.

1149
01:13:35,200 --> 01:13:37,170
What?

1150
01:13:38,830 --> 01:13:41,370
Thank you, Mom.

1151
01:14:04,190 --> 01:14:05,860
Wait here.

1152
01:14:09,170 --> 01:14:11,230
What--What's going on?

1153
01:14:13,540 --> 01:14:16,640
Just be patient, champ.
Just be patient.

1154
01:14:16,670 --> 01:14:18,670
Ready.

1155
01:14:18,710 --> 01:14:20,580
Close your eyes.

1156
01:14:23,510 --> 01:14:25,780
Open your eyes.

1157
01:14:25,810 --> 01:14:27,550
Happy birthday!

1158
01:14:27,580 --> 01:14:29,590
Happy birthday.

1159
01:14:29,620 --> 01:14:32,590
I know it's a little late
due to bad behavior,

1160
01:14:32,620 --> 01:14:34,290
but better late
than never, right?

1161
01:14:36,490 --> 01:14:39,430
Right.

1162
01:14:39,460 --> 01:14:42,800
What are you waiting for?
They're not gonna blow
themselves out.

1163
01:14:47,600 --> 01:14:50,540
[blowing weakly]

1164
01:14:58,350 --> 01:15:00,750
Um, sorry.

1165
01:15:00,780 --> 01:15:02,650
I must be a little tired.

1166
01:15:07,990 --> 01:15:09,690
Honey, they're--

1167
01:15:09,730 --> 01:15:11,260
Honey,
they're trick candles.

1168
01:15:11,290 --> 01:15:12,730
It was your father's idea.

1169
01:15:12,760 --> 01:15:15,360
Hey, it might have been my idea,
but who bought them?

1170
01:15:15,400 --> 01:15:16,870
Yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah.

1171
01:15:16,900 --> 01:15:18,730
Here we go.
Here we go.

1172
01:15:18,770 --> 01:15:20,740
Let's get those out.
That's coming out.

1173
01:15:20,770 --> 01:15:23,310
Ooh.
Whoo.

1174
01:15:24,370 --> 01:15:26,710
[blowing]

1175
01:15:27,840 --> 01:15:29,750
All right, sweetie.
Yeah.

1176
01:15:29,780 --> 01:15:32,210
Which piece do you want?

1177
01:15:36,450 --> 01:15:39,320
Um...

1178
01:15:49,300 --> 01:15:51,770
How about...

1179
01:15:56,970 --> 01:15:58,940
[Mark laughing]
all of it?

1180
01:15:58,970 --> 01:16:01,280
[Alice laughing]

1181
01:16:18,030 --> 01:16:19,960
What's wrong, Mom?

1182
01:16:22,330 --> 01:16:24,430
I don't know
what to say.

1183
01:16:24,470 --> 01:16:28,270
I've waited for this
for a year--

1184
01:16:29,440 --> 01:16:33,640
in the hall, in my room--

1185
01:16:33,680 --> 01:16:36,780
wondering when you
were gonna come back,

1186
01:16:38,780 --> 01:16:41,520
when we were all
gonna be sitting here.

1187
01:16:42,980 --> 01:16:46,020
I just don't know
what to say.

1188
01:16:46,050 --> 01:16:48,590
You don't have to.

1189
01:16:49,860 --> 01:16:52,430
I've come back.

1190
01:17:01,470 --> 01:17:04,040
Can't I sleep
without them tonight?

1191
01:17:04,070 --> 01:17:05,710
Like we talked about
with Dr. Nance?

1192
01:17:05,740 --> 01:17:07,440
I'm ready.

1193
01:17:07,480 --> 01:17:08,780
I know, but...

1194
01:17:08,810 --> 01:17:10,710
Well, I--I think it's fair.

1195
01:17:10,750 --> 01:17:13,080
What if he falls out of bed?
He could fall out of bed.

1196
01:17:13,110 --> 01:17:15,480
I'm not a little boy
anymore, Mom.

1197
01:17:15,520 --> 01:17:18,420
I'm 19 now.
I'm not gonna fall out of bed.

1198
01:17:18,450 --> 01:17:20,560
We did make a deal.

1199
01:17:20,590 --> 01:17:22,390
Fine.
We did.

1200
01:17:22,420 --> 01:17:26,290
Okay, but if you need anything,
I will be right outside, okay?

1201
01:17:27,360 --> 01:17:29,470
Good night.

1202
01:17:35,400 --> 01:17:37,770
[floor creaking]

1203
01:18:14,040 --> 01:18:16,080
[soft clangs]

1204
01:18:20,950 --> 01:18:22,120
[wheel squeaks]

1205
01:18:25,120 --> 01:18:27,460
[soft clangs]

1206
01:18:34,160 --> 01:18:36,930
[wheels squeaking]

1207
01:18:38,130 --> 01:18:39,570
[squeaking continues]

1208
01:18:41,440 --> 01:18:43,470
[panting]

1209
01:18:45,140 --> 01:18:46,980
Timmy?

1210
01:18:50,110 --> 01:18:53,080
I was thirsty.
I'm just getting some water.

1211
01:18:53,110 --> 01:18:55,450
That's okay, honey.
I'll get it for you.

1212
01:18:55,480 --> 01:18:57,590
No, I've got it.

1213
01:18:57,620 --> 01:18:59,590
You can go back to bed.

1214
01:18:59,620 --> 01:19:02,420
Only if I can help you
back to yours.

1215
01:19:08,500 --> 01:19:10,530
We've come a long way
since then, haven't we?

1216
01:19:13,130 --> 01:19:16,610
You don't remember
that yet, do you?

1217
01:19:16,640 --> 01:19:18,710
How you first died.

1218
01:19:19,980 --> 01:19:21,780
You thought you were
a burden.

1219
01:19:21,810 --> 01:19:25,780
You didn't wanna be,
and so you tried
to sneak out.

1220
01:19:25,810 --> 01:19:27,780
You saw us coming,
you tried to run,

1221
01:19:27,820 --> 01:19:31,890
and your body
couldn't take it.

1222
01:19:31,920 --> 01:19:33,720
You fell.

1223
01:19:35,520 --> 01:19:38,490
We stayed with you
for days,

1224
01:19:38,530 --> 01:19:41,500
waiting for you
to come back.

1225
01:19:41,530 --> 01:19:44,130
We didn't know
it would take a year.

1226
01:19:49,270 --> 01:19:51,610
That is over now.

1227
01:19:51,640 --> 01:19:52,910
We are passed it.

1228
01:19:52,940 --> 01:19:54,610
Let's get you back to bed.

1229
01:19:54,640 --> 01:19:57,480
Oh, give me your water.
I'll hold it for you.

1230
01:20:00,950 --> 01:20:02,850
Were you trying
to sneak out again?

1231
01:20:02,880 --> 01:20:04,850
No. I just...

1232
01:20:04,890 --> 01:20:07,220
I just forgot my glass
in the kitchen.

1233
01:20:07,260 --> 01:20:09,530
But I don't understand.

1234
01:20:09,560 --> 01:20:11,260
We've been good.

1235
01:20:11,290 --> 01:20:14,130
You're not a burden anymore.
Why would you...

1236
01:20:16,600 --> 01:20:18,700
You're not fully back.
You lied.

1237
01:20:18,730 --> 01:20:20,770
Let me go.
I will not!

1238
01:20:20,800 --> 01:20:22,700
We trusted you,
and you lied.

1239
01:20:22,740 --> 01:20:25,540
You said you were better.
We celebrated your birthday.

1240
01:20:25,570 --> 01:20:27,280
I'm not your son!

1241
01:20:27,310 --> 01:20:29,580
You are horrible, awful!

1242
01:20:29,610 --> 01:20:31,880
Only a horrible child
would say such a thing!

1243
01:20:31,910 --> 01:20:35,920
What's going on? Alice?
Mark, he's trying to leave.

1244
01:20:35,950 --> 01:20:37,750
Don't turn him against you,
all right?
No.

1245
01:20:37,790 --> 01:20:38,850
Alice--
No. No.

1246
01:20:38,890 --> 01:20:40,690
Let's talk about it,
all right?

1247
01:20:40,720 --> 01:20:42,860
Let's see what the problem is.
Sweetie--Sweetie...

1248
01:20:42,890 --> 01:20:45,530
Everybody take a deep breath.
Listen to me. Listen to me.

1249
01:20:45,560 --> 01:20:48,900
Maybe we need to slow down.
Let me go!

1250
01:20:48,930 --> 01:20:51,230
I'm not Timmy!
[body thuds]

1251
01:20:52,570 --> 01:20:54,540
He's okay, right, Mark?

1252
01:20:54,570 --> 01:20:56,940
Tell me.
Tell me he's okay.

1253
01:20:58,770 --> 01:21:01,040
Tell me he's okay!

1254
01:21:27,300 --> 01:21:29,200
Don't say it.

1255
01:21:31,110 --> 01:21:33,880
Alice, please.

1256
01:21:33,910 --> 01:21:37,610
It's only been 10 hours.

1257
01:21:38,710 --> 01:21:40,980
Ten hours!

1258
01:21:41,020 --> 01:21:43,620
Last time,
it took a year.

1259
01:21:44,920 --> 01:21:46,890
So don't say it.

1260
01:21:50,330 --> 01:21:51,760
No.

1261
01:21:53,190 --> 01:21:54,630
No!

1262
01:22:18,290 --> 01:22:20,790
[Alex]
Come back.

1263
01:22:20,820 --> 01:22:22,690
Come back!

1264
01:22:25,730 --> 01:22:28,930
[sighs]
I'm not dead.

1265
01:22:28,960 --> 01:22:31,730
I'm still alive.

1266
01:22:33,030 --> 01:22:37,240
Please, please come back.

1267
01:22:38,810 --> 01:22:40,680
Please come back,
Mom and Dad.

1268
01:22:40,710 --> 01:22:43,010
I'm still waiting.
[sobbing]

1269
01:22:43,040 --> 01:22:46,010
I so want you to come back.

1270
01:22:46,050 --> 01:22:48,620
I want you to come back.

1271
01:22:53,790 --> 01:22:56,660
[footsteps approaching]

1272
01:22:56,690 --> 01:22:58,990
What are you doing in here?
I told you not to come in here.

1273
01:22:59,030 --> 01:23:01,300
And I told you
not to steal.

1274
01:23:01,330 --> 01:23:02,800
But I need that,
Daddy.

1275
01:23:02,830 --> 01:23:04,800
I'm sure you've convinced
yourself of that.

1276
01:23:04,830 --> 01:23:06,870
Fine.
I'll just take these.

1277
01:23:06,900 --> 01:23:08,940
That's all right.
I've got everything
backed up on disc.

1278
01:23:08,970 --> 01:23:11,040
I don't need those anymore.
Holy shit!

1279
01:23:11,070 --> 01:23:12,840
Who did you steal this from
and why?

1280
01:23:12,870 --> 01:23:14,810
I know him!
He's your patient?

1281
01:23:14,840 --> 01:23:17,680
Josie, you're not
gonna get it back.

1282
01:23:17,710 --> 01:23:19,310
Stop trying to change
the subject from yourself.

1283
01:23:19,350 --> 01:23:22,350
That's the reason
you're not getting
any better.

1284
01:23:22,380 --> 01:23:24,190
[gasps]
Oh, my God!
What?

1285
01:23:24,220 --> 01:23:25,720
Spider! Oh, my God!
In the shadows!
Where?

1286
01:23:25,750 --> 01:23:27,760
Kill it, kill it!

1287
01:23:29,930 --> 01:23:31,830
That's a nice try.

1288
01:23:31,860 --> 01:23:33,760
Give me the file.

1289
01:23:33,800 --> 01:23:37,770
Give me the file
and the box.

1290
01:23:37,800 --> 01:23:39,430
I'm sorry, Dad.

1291
01:23:39,470 --> 01:23:42,800
I need to go think about
why I do what I do.

1292
01:23:42,840 --> 01:23:44,440
You better.
All right.

1293
01:23:50,910 --> 01:23:52,850
[engine starts]

1294
01:24:15,870 --> 01:24:17,810
Alex!

1295
01:24:31,290 --> 01:24:33,220
Alex!

1296
01:24:50,940 --> 01:24:53,040
[Alex]
Come back!

1297
01:24:54,940 --> 01:24:56,080
Alex?

1298
01:24:56,110 --> 01:24:58,150
[banging]

1299
01:24:58,180 --> 01:24:59,780
Holy shit!

1300
01:25:07,820 --> 01:25:10,090
Please.

1301
01:25:10,130 --> 01:25:12,190
Please come back.

1302
01:25:20,200 --> 01:25:21,970
[thudding]

1303
01:25:28,880 --> 01:25:29,980
Mom?

1304
01:25:30,010 --> 01:25:32,050
No, Josie.

1305
01:25:32,080 --> 01:25:34,450
What the hell happened?

1306
01:25:35,550 --> 01:25:37,890
You have to leave.
I have to wait for them.

1307
01:25:37,920 --> 01:25:40,120
Uh, okay, sure.

1308
01:25:40,160 --> 01:25:41,120
No!

1309
01:25:41,160 --> 01:25:43,090
No, I have to wait
for them.

1310
01:25:49,600 --> 01:25:51,970
You don't understand.
It's my fault.

1311
01:25:52,000 --> 01:25:54,540
What? No, it's not your fault.
Come on.

1312
01:25:54,570 --> 01:25:56,910
You don't know what I did.

1313
01:25:57,970 --> 01:26:00,010
You don't know.

1314
01:26:00,040 --> 01:26:02,040
I'm horrible.

1315
01:26:07,020 --> 01:26:08,880
It was an accident.

1316
01:26:09,990 --> 01:26:11,950
You know that.

1317
01:26:11,990 --> 01:26:14,460
They're not coming back.

1318
01:26:14,490 --> 01:26:17,960
The people that are coming back,
on the other hand, are psychos.

1319
01:26:17,990 --> 01:26:20,460
Okay?
Which means we need to go.

1320
01:26:20,500 --> 01:26:22,960
[car approaching]

1321
01:26:26,270 --> 01:26:28,100
[Alex]
The front door's over here.

1322
01:26:35,010 --> 01:26:37,510
[keys jingling]
They're back.

1323
01:27:13,550 --> 01:27:15,180
[Mark]
All right.
It's all set up.

1324
01:27:15,220 --> 01:27:18,090
I'll be back
to check on you
in a few minutes.

1325
01:27:19,720 --> 01:27:21,990
We were good,
weren't we?

1326
01:27:24,230 --> 01:27:26,490
Good to him?

1327
01:27:29,130 --> 01:27:31,130
What are we gonna do?

1328
01:27:35,170 --> 01:27:37,110
I'm gonna go get some boxes,

1329
01:27:37,140 --> 01:27:39,040
and you're gonna
watch Dr. Alred.

1330
01:27:39,070 --> 01:27:40,440
Honey, can't we
check the garden?

1331
01:27:40,480 --> 01:27:42,110
Alice...
Maybe he just...

1332
01:27:42,140 --> 01:27:44,010
Alice...

1333
01:27:52,750 --> 01:27:54,190
[door closes]

1334
01:27:56,360 --> 01:27:58,330
[TV on]

1335
01:27:58,360 --> 01:28:01,100
[Dr. Alred on TV]
Hello, I'm Dr. Alred.

1336
01:28:01,130 --> 01:28:03,200
This must be
a very trying time.

1337
01:28:03,230 --> 01:28:05,200
You have to remember

1338
01:28:05,230 --> 01:28:08,340
that what you're going through
is normal.

1339
01:28:08,370 --> 01:28:10,970
Anyone who encounters
such tragedy

1340
01:28:11,010 --> 01:28:13,410
goes through
these very feelings.

1341
01:28:13,440 --> 01:28:19,050
Many familiar things
will remind you of your loss,

1342
01:28:19,080 --> 01:28:22,650
but do not run
from these objects.

1343
01:28:22,680 --> 01:28:24,590
Embrace them.

1344
01:28:24,620 --> 01:28:26,590
They'll serve
as a constant reminder

1345
01:28:26,620 --> 01:28:30,590
and help keep their spirit
alive within your home,

1346
01:28:30,630 --> 01:28:33,760
even as maybe
you try to forget.

1347
01:28:33,790 --> 01:28:35,760
If you run,

1348
01:28:35,800 --> 01:28:39,500
you're erasing
their memory,

1349
01:28:39,530 --> 01:28:43,100
which is the last thing
you wanna do.

1350
01:28:49,580 --> 01:28:52,050
That's why he forgot.

1351
01:28:53,710 --> 01:28:57,050
He didn't have anything
to remember us by.

1352
01:28:57,090 --> 01:28:59,690
He needs something--

1353
01:28:59,720 --> 01:29:02,060
any-anything to help him
remember.

1354
01:29:02,090 --> 01:29:05,390
Anything before Mark
packs him away.

1355
01:29:07,160 --> 01:29:11,600
Something that he'll see
right when he comes back.

1356
01:29:21,780 --> 01:29:24,050
To leave under with him.

1357
01:29:32,850 --> 01:29:35,190
There needs to be
no doubt.

1358
01:29:37,360 --> 01:29:40,060
[chuckles]

1359
01:29:40,100 --> 01:29:41,600
The cake.

1360
01:29:44,230 --> 01:29:46,500
He would never forget
his own nose.

1361
01:29:48,500 --> 01:29:50,110
Um...

1362
01:30:04,590 --> 01:30:07,360
This is perfect.

1363
01:30:07,390 --> 01:30:09,120
What else?

1364
01:30:09,160 --> 01:30:11,660
What else, what else
what else, what else?

1365
01:30:14,560 --> 01:30:16,130
Okay.

1366
01:30:27,710 --> 01:30:31,150
Mark, he's back!
Get out here!

1367
01:30:31,180 --> 01:30:33,150
[door opens]
[Mark]
What's wrong?

1368
01:30:33,180 --> 01:30:35,280
[Alice]
Nothing. Everything's right.

1369
01:30:35,320 --> 01:30:37,690
Guard the front door.
He might be scared.

1370
01:30:37,720 --> 01:30:40,560
What are you talking about?
He's back! He's come back!

1371
01:30:40,590 --> 01:30:43,560
On the same day!
He-He came back for the cake!

1372
01:30:43,590 --> 01:30:46,560
I was slicing a piece
so that he would have
something to remember,

1373
01:30:46,590 --> 01:30:48,730
which is what
we didn't do before.

1374
01:30:48,760 --> 01:30:51,300
Alice--Alice, stop.
No! N-No!

1375
01:30:51,330 --> 01:30:53,300
Go! Go look yourself!

1376
01:30:53,330 --> 01:30:55,270
Go on.

1377
01:30:55,300 --> 01:30:57,540
[sniffling]

1378
01:30:57,570 --> 01:31:00,280
Timmy? Honey?

1379
01:31:00,310 --> 01:31:03,410
Come on out.
Don't be scared.

1380
01:31:03,440 --> 01:31:05,580
We're your parents.
That's right.

1381
01:31:05,610 --> 01:31:09,180
Your-- Your mom
and your dad.

1382
01:31:10,250 --> 01:31:13,650
Timmy, honey,
where are you?

1383
01:31:15,290 --> 01:31:17,830
He was dead.
He was dead.

1384
01:31:17,860 --> 01:31:20,200
No, not for us.

1385
01:31:21,260 --> 01:31:23,200
Well, where is he?

1386
01:31:23,230 --> 01:31:24,670
I'm gonna go
and check out back,

1387
01:31:24,700 --> 01:31:26,770
and you stay
by the door.

1388
01:31:28,700 --> 01:31:30,370
Timmy?

1389
01:31:30,410 --> 01:31:34,840
Timmy? Timmy?

1390
01:31:35,910 --> 01:31:37,880
Timmy.

1391
01:31:40,820 --> 01:31:43,550
The hall.
We can get out a back window.

1392
01:31:45,990 --> 01:31:48,590
Timmy.

1393
01:31:50,890 --> 01:31:53,890
What's wrong with your feet?
Nothing. I'm fine.

1394
01:31:53,930 --> 01:31:56,200
[door opens]
[Alice]
Timmy?

1395
01:31:58,300 --> 01:32:00,240
Timmy?

1396
01:32:00,270 --> 01:32:02,300
Where?
[door closes]

1397
01:32:02,340 --> 01:32:03,900
The closet.

1398
01:32:13,350 --> 01:32:15,320
She won't look in here?

1399
01:32:15,350 --> 01:32:18,220
Mark won't let her.
He says that this is his place.

1400
01:32:19,620 --> 01:32:23,820
Come on out, honey.
It's Mom.

1401
01:32:25,890 --> 01:32:28,660
Timmy, sweetie,
where are you?

1402
01:32:28,700 --> 01:32:30,930
Come on, honey.

1403
01:32:30,970 --> 01:32:34,670
Quit playing around.
Stop hiding from me.

1404
01:32:36,670 --> 01:32:38,870
Timmy, this isn't
funny anymore.

1405
01:32:38,910 --> 01:32:40,740
We're getting scared.

1406
01:32:40,780 --> 01:32:43,410
Maybe we should look
down the street.
He might've left.

1407
01:32:43,440 --> 01:32:46,310
No, he is in this house.
I know it.

1408
01:32:46,350 --> 01:32:48,780
Timmy, I don't wanna punish you
on your first day back,

1409
01:32:48,820 --> 01:32:51,350
but if you're not out here
by the time I count to five,

1410
01:32:51,390 --> 01:32:53,450
then you have only
yourself to blame.

1411
01:32:53,490 --> 01:32:56,290
One,

1412
01:32:56,320 --> 01:32:57,830
two,

1413
01:32:57,860 --> 01:32:59,390
three,

1414
01:32:59,430 --> 01:33:00,700
four...

1415
01:33:00,730 --> 01:33:03,530
Timmy, come out right now!

1416
01:33:04,700 --> 01:33:08,500
Oh, my God! He's hurt!

1417
01:33:11,970 --> 01:33:14,610
That's why he's not coming out.
He's too hurt.

1418
01:33:15,680 --> 01:33:17,310
[door opens]

1419
01:33:23,520 --> 01:33:24,950
Timmy?

1420
01:33:26,850 --> 01:33:28,320
Honey?

1421
01:33:29,460 --> 01:33:31,730
Do you remember
what this place is?

1422
01:33:32,790 --> 01:33:35,830
It's your father's office.

1423
01:33:35,860 --> 01:33:39,470
He works from here because
we wanted to be home
when you came back.

1424
01:33:45,840 --> 01:33:47,910
Timmy, open up.

1425
01:33:50,950 --> 01:33:53,450
Honey, I know you're hurt.

1426
01:33:53,480 --> 01:33:55,650
I just wanna help you.
I wanna make you feel better.

1427
01:33:55,680 --> 01:34:00,050
I'm your mother.
That's what moms do.

1428
01:34:00,090 --> 01:34:03,860
We would never have left
if we knew you were gonna
come back so soon.

1429
01:34:06,460 --> 01:34:09,400
I'm sorry, Mom.
[whispers]
Oh, my God.

1430
01:34:10,530 --> 01:34:13,370
Oh, honey.

1431
01:34:15,070 --> 01:34:17,970
We're not mad at you.

1432
01:34:18,010 --> 01:34:20,340
Just open the door.

1433
01:34:23,410 --> 01:34:24,980
Timmy!

1434
01:34:27,880 --> 01:34:29,780
Open up now!

1435
01:34:29,820 --> 01:34:31,120
[bangs on door]

1436
01:34:31,150 --> 01:34:33,050
All right. Then we're
gonna do it the hard way.

1437
01:34:33,090 --> 01:34:34,720
Mark, give me the keys
to your office.

1438
01:34:34,760 --> 01:34:36,420
Give them to me.
Alice, please.

1439
01:34:36,460 --> 01:34:38,060
Timmy!

1440
01:34:38,090 --> 01:34:39,890
Timmy, open the door!

1441
01:34:39,930 --> 01:34:41,730
Timmy!

1442
01:34:41,760 --> 01:34:43,400
Mark, hurry up.

1443
01:34:43,430 --> 01:34:44,870
Alice...

1444
01:34:58,810 --> 01:35:00,550
Honey,

1445
01:35:00,580 --> 01:35:03,920
you don't need
to hide anymore.

1446
01:35:03,950 --> 01:35:07,120
I'm here,
and so is your father.

1447
01:35:09,460 --> 01:35:12,660
He hung up all these
clippings for you.

1448
01:35:12,690 --> 01:35:15,130
That's how much
he loves you.

1449
01:35:19,430 --> 01:35:21,640
I know you have
a lot of questions.

1450
01:35:21,670 --> 01:35:25,540
I'm gonna try and answer them
better than before.

1451
01:35:26,670 --> 01:35:28,480
Timmy...

1452
01:35:30,480 --> 01:35:32,110
[screams]

1453
01:35:32,150 --> 01:35:34,920
Alice? Alice?
[door opens]

1454
01:35:36,950 --> 01:35:38,920
Sit me down.

1455
01:35:38,950 --> 01:35:40,920
[Alice]
He's got someone with him!

1456
01:35:40,960 --> 01:35:42,560
She's strong.

1457
01:35:42,590 --> 01:35:44,590
Stealing from us.

1458
01:35:44,630 --> 01:35:46,590
Timmy, who is this?
Do you know her?

1459
01:35:46,630 --> 01:35:48,600
Yeah, she's my friend, Josie.

1460
01:35:48,630 --> 01:35:50,600
You--You don't know
a Josie.

1461
01:35:50,630 --> 01:35:52,970
You never knew a Josie.
He knows me.

1462
01:35:53,000 --> 01:35:54,800
You did this to him.
You ruined him.

1463
01:35:54,840 --> 01:35:56,670
You were the first person
he saw.

1464
01:35:56,700 --> 01:35:59,810
Timmy,
you don't know her.

1465
01:35:59,840 --> 01:36:01,980
You know me
and your father.

1466
01:36:02,010 --> 01:36:03,710
You're not his parents.

1467
01:36:03,740 --> 01:36:05,710
Tell them what happened
to your parents, Alex.

1468
01:36:05,750 --> 01:36:07,580
Nothing happened.
Nothing happened to them.

1469
01:36:07,620 --> 01:36:09,050
He just doesn't remember us.

1470
01:36:09,080 --> 01:36:10,690
Tell her, Alex.
He just doesn't
remember us.

1471
01:36:10,720 --> 01:36:12,490
Tell her, Alex!

1472
01:36:12,520 --> 01:36:15,190
I think it is time
for you to leave.

1473
01:36:16,990 --> 01:36:19,490
They le--

1474
01:36:19,530 --> 01:36:21,460
They left.

1475
01:36:22,930 --> 01:36:25,600
They were looking
for me.

1476
01:36:27,540 --> 01:36:31,040
If I...hadn't left,

1477
01:36:32,670 --> 01:36:34,710
they wouldn't have died.

1478
01:36:38,550 --> 01:36:40,950
But it wasn't my fault.

1479
01:36:40,980 --> 01:36:44,020
It was-- It wasn't...

1480
01:36:44,050 --> 01:36:46,090
It wasn't my fault.

1481
01:36:47,560 --> 01:36:50,220
[Mark]
That's why
you told Alice

1482
01:36:50,260 --> 01:36:52,230
that you couldn't
remember them?

1483
01:36:52,260 --> 01:36:54,860
That's not it, Mark.
Is that why?

1484
01:36:54,900 --> 01:36:57,800
It's because you
filled his head with that.

1485
01:36:57,830 --> 01:37:00,870
She was there when we--
when we weren't.

1486
01:37:00,900 --> 01:37:03,600
We should've been there
for him.

1487
01:37:03,640 --> 01:37:06,540
We should've been there for...

1488
01:37:06,570 --> 01:37:09,080
But we are now,
and that is what is important.

1489
01:37:09,110 --> 01:37:12,980
Remember who you are,
not what she tells you to.

1490
01:37:14,050 --> 01:37:17,550
See? His name is Alex.

1491
01:37:17,590 --> 01:37:21,160
Tell her, Alex.
Tell her why you came here.

1492
01:37:21,190 --> 01:37:23,090
You saw her, right?
You followed them.

1493
01:37:23,120 --> 01:37:26,090
No, no, no.
You stole him from me.

1494
01:37:26,130 --> 01:37:28,530
I work at the library.

1495
01:37:28,560 --> 01:37:30,530
You come in all the time.
I saw you there,

1496
01:37:30,570 --> 01:37:34,030
and you saw me once,
watching you.

1497
01:37:34,070 --> 01:37:36,670
I tried telling you.
[Alice]
No, no, no, no, no.

1498
01:37:36,700 --> 01:37:37,740
I did.

1499
01:37:37,770 --> 01:37:38,710
No.

1500
01:37:40,780 --> 01:37:43,040
Timmy, if you don't remember...

1501
01:37:46,050 --> 01:37:48,180
then I have to start all over

1502
01:37:48,220 --> 01:37:50,120
and show you things
to help you remember,

1503
01:37:50,150 --> 01:37:51,690
and I don't wanna do that.

1504
01:37:54,190 --> 01:37:56,890
Please don't make me do that.

1505
01:37:56,920 --> 01:37:59,660
Please remember.

1506
01:38:01,160 --> 01:38:03,230
Don't make me do that, Timmy!

1507
01:38:08,140 --> 01:38:09,600
Come on.

1508
01:38:09,640 --> 01:38:11,270
[Alice]
No!

1509
01:38:11,310 --> 01:38:14,710
What are you doing?
You're letting him leave!

1510
01:38:14,740 --> 01:38:17,650
His keys!
What do you take me for?

1511
01:38:17,680 --> 01:38:19,650
No! No! No!
Let me go!

1512
01:38:19,680 --> 01:38:22,220
What are you doing?
You're letting him leave!

1513
01:38:22,250 --> 01:38:24,220
Timmy! He's leaving!

1514
01:38:24,250 --> 01:38:26,890
Let me go!
Timmy! Honey!

1515
01:38:26,920 --> 01:38:28,890
Stay! It's-- It's okay!

1516
01:38:28,920 --> 01:38:31,130
It's okay. Stay.

1517
01:38:31,160 --> 01:38:34,600
[Alice sobbing]

1518
01:38:34,630 --> 01:38:36,630
[engine starts]

1519
01:38:37,930 --> 01:38:39,630
Baby!

1520
01:38:39,670 --> 01:38:42,170
[car departing]

1521
01:38:47,780 --> 01:38:49,810
Our son is gone.

1522
01:38:52,110 --> 01:38:53,750
Our son is gone.

1523
01:38:53,780 --> 01:38:56,720
[sobbing continues]

